<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton Takes to the Stage  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- After more than seven years of enduring
barbs as first lady, Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton got
her chance Saturday night to offer up zingers of her own as she
took the stage -- with a carpet bag in hand -- at the nation's oldest
continuous political gridiron show.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just like every other New Yorker with Secret Service
protection,'' said the first lady, who moved into New York in
January.
</P>
<P>
   She noted she was already on her second opponent, and provided
the audience of 500 at the 100th annual Legislative Correspondents
Association dinner in Albany with a slide show of home photos -- all
of them showing her wearing a New York Yankees' hat.
</P>
<P>
   She was even wearing the hat, thanks to a digital enhancement,
during her husband's first inaugural walk down Pennsylvania Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Republican opponent in the Senate race, Rep. Rick
Lazio, attended the show as well, but declined an invitation to
speak. Aides said Lazio's late entry into the race, after New York
City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani quit the campaign last month to deal
with prostate cancer, had left them with too little time to prepare
for the appearance.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. John Sweeney, a former top aide to Gov. George Pataki,
delivered the Republican response at the conclusion of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney showed a video takeoff on the hit movie ''The
Gladiator,'' in which Clinton was ''Statelessius'' in a fight
against ''Split Lipitus.'' In Sweeney's video, the gladiator with
the split lip -- a reference to Lazio's fall in a recent parade that
left him with a fat lip -- won the battle.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Lazio shook hands before the show began but spoke
only briefly and sat at opposite sides of the front table.
</P>
<P>
   The $200-a-person black-tie gala raises money for charity and
attracts the movers and shakers of New York politics and
government.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's turn on the stage came only after reporters who
write about state government had a chance to skewer her and other
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Karen DeWitt of the New York Public Radio Network portrayed
Clinton in a musical skit, singing to the tune of ''Can't Take My
Mind Off of You'':
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just too crass to be true, even said I was a Jew.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll do whatever it takes,
</P>
<P>
   ''Cause my self-worth is at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   The LCA show was held at the Empire State Plaza Convention
Center adjacent to the state Capitol.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 0003 </TRAILER>
