<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton takes stage at political satire show  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - After more than seven years of enduring
barbs as first lady, Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton got
her chance Saturday night to offer up zingers of her own as she
appeared at the nation's oldest continuous political gridiron show,
taking the stage with a carpetbag in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just like every other New Yorker with Secret Service
protection,'' the first lady, who moved into New York in January,
told the audience of more than 500 people.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that she was already on ''my second opponent,'' Clinton
provided the audience with a slide show of home photos titled ''The
Woman from Chappaqua,'' a play on her husband's 1992 presidential
campaign video ''The Man from Hope.'' The first lady's photos,
including one of her as a child and another of her as an adult
meeting the Pope, showed her wearing a New York Yankees' hat.
</P>
<P>
   ''He really liked my hat,'' the first lady said of the Pope's
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   She was even wearing the hat, thanks to a digital enhancement,
during her husband's first inaugural walk down Pennsylvania Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady came under fire early in the campaign when she
claimed she had always rooted for the Yankees in the American
League, even while her main allegiance was to the National League's
Chicago Cubs. She grew up in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was and someday will be permitted to be a Yankees fan,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was one of the guest speakers at the 100th annual
Legislative Correspondents Association dinner and show in Albany.
She is seeking the Senate seat being vacated this year by fellow
Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Republican opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island,
attended the show as well, but declined an invitation to speak.
Aides said Lazio's late entry into the race, after New York City
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani quit the campaign last month to deal with
prostate cancer, had left them with too little time to prepare for
the appearance.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. John Sweeney, a former top aide to Gov. George Pataki,
delivered the Republican response at the conclusion of the show.
Sweeney showed a video takeoff on the hit movie ''The Gladiator,''
in which Clinton was ''Statelessius'' in a fight against ''Split
Lipitus.'' In Sweeney's video, the gladiator with the split lip - a
reference to Lazio's fall in a recent parade that left him with a
fat lip - won the battle.
</P>
<P>
   Seated at the head table, Clinton and Lazio shook hands before
the show began. They spoke only briefly and sat at opposite sides
of the round table for 10.
</P>
<P>
   The $200-a-person black-tie gala raises money for charity and
attracts the movers and shakers of New York politics and
government. Among others, the crowd for Saturday night's event
included Pataki and state Comptroller H. Carl McCall, a potential
Democratic candidate for governor in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   After five years of being a guest speaker at the LCA show,
Pataki decided not to speak at this year's event.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's turn on the stage came only after reporters
covering the state government had a chance to skewer her and other
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   The role of Hillary Clinton was played in Saturday night's show
by Karen DeWitt of the New York Public Radio Network. Clinton, who
laughed at most of the acts, didn't seem as amused when DeWitt
sang, to the tune of ''Can't Take My Mind Off of You'':
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just too crass to be true, even said I was a Jew.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll do whatever it takes,
</P>
<P>
   ''Cause my self-worth is at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   At intermission, the first lady went backstage and shook hands
with cast members. When she met DeWitt, Clinton smiled and said,
''Nice job.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore's claim that he was out of the room
during a key White House discussion of questionable fund-raising
plans because he had consumed too much ice tea and had to use the
restroom was also grist for the reporters' mill. Erik Kriss of the
Syracuse Herald-Journal/Post Standard played the role of the vice
president and sang to the tune of Kenny Rodgers' ''The Gambler:''
</P>
<P>
   ''You got to know when to wee-wee when you're the VP.
</P>
<P>
   ''Know when to leave the room and run out to the can.
</P>
<P>
   ''When subpoenas start a fallin', just tell 'em nature's callin'
</P>
<P>
   ''That's why you don't know the first thing 'bout the crooked
plans.''
</P>
<P>
   The LCA show was held at the Empire State Plaza Convention
Center adjacent to the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislative Correspondents Alumni Association's Walter T.
Brown award for excellence in reporting over the past year went to
Paul Ertelt of the Watertown Daily Times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-11-00 0010 </TRAILER>
