<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brussels Police, Soccer Fans Clash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Police in riot gear fired tear gas
Sunday to disperse thousands of rowdy soccer fans in the center of
Brussels, hours after Belgium beat Sweden 2-1 in the opening match
of the Euro 2000 soccer championship.
</P>
<P>
   Streets around the Grand' Place, the Neo-classic central square,
were cordoned off late Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   What began as a celebration by flag-waving, singing soccer fans
turned nasty when bottles and glasses were thrown at police who
responded with charges and volleys of tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of soccer fans filled the center of town after the
Belgium-Sweden match in the King Baudouin Stadium on the northern
outskirts of Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Police fired tear gas to disperse crowds that tried to break
through police lines to reach the Grand' Place.
</P>
<P>
   The downtown clashes were in sharp contrast to the order that
was maintained around the stadium before and during the match that
was attended by the royal families of Belgium and the Netherlands,
co-hosts of the Euro 2000 event.
</P>
<P>
   Before the match, two dozen people were taken into custody in
various places across Belgium on charges of scalping tickets
outside the stadium, police said.
</P>
<P>
   They included four Germans who were detained as they entered
Belgium with 107 tickets for several Euro 2000 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Belgium-Sweden match marked the start of the 16-team soccer
tournament in a game played before King Albert of Belgium and Queen
Beatrix of the Netherlands and a crowd of 50,000 at King Baudouin
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Belgians, sharing the role of tournament host with the
Netherlands, were backed by goals Bart Goor and Emile Mpenza and
survived a blunder by goalkeeper Filip de Wilde in the day's only
game.
</P>
<P>
   Goor scored two minutes before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds after halftime, Emile Mpenza took a pass from Branko
Strupar and struck with a shot high into the net. The goal meant
that within four minutes on the clock, Sweden yielded more goals
than during its entire qualifying campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament, which ends July 2 in Rotterdam, will be played
amid unprecedented police numbers, with English, German and Dutch
fans targeted by authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Border police on Saturday stopped two dozen known and suspected
English hooligans from traveling to Belgium and the Netherlands.
Three drunken fans arriving from England also were sent back.
</P>
<P>
   In all, some two dozen Englishmen, either convicted for hooligan
violence or suspected of spawning such violence were kept in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, three games were scheduled: World Cup champion France
against Denmark; the Netherlands, the title favorite, against the
Czech Republic, the runner-up in the last Euros in 1996; and Italy
against Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Germany does not play until Monday when it
meets Romania.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 0034 </TRAILER>
