<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, June 11, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Devils 2, Stars 1, 2OT
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- The Devils' Jason Arnott ripped a shot from the left circle
past Dallas goaltender Ed Belfour 8:20 into the second overtime, ending a second
consecutive tension-filled overtime game -- and the Dallas Stars' Stanley Cup
run -- with a 2-1 New Jersy victory Saturday night. Arnott one-timed Patrik
Elias' shot past Belfour as the Devils prevented the Stars from forcing a Game 7
Monday in New Jersey.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Assad's Son Clears Hurdle for Leadership
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- Within hours after the death of President Hafez Assad
Saturday, Syria's parliament overwhelmingly voted to amend an article in the
constitution that requires the head of state to be at least 40 years old,
clearing the way for Assad's son, Bashar, to assume the presidency. The
legislators voted to lower the age to 34. Bashar is 34. Then parliament
adjourned until June 25. Assad had been grooming Bashar for future leadership,
but the British-educated ophthalmologist has held no major political office.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Provincial Capital in Solomon Islands Seized
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HONIARA, Solomon Islands (AP) -- Bringing a third warring faction into the
volatile crisis, militants seized a provincial capital in the western Solomon
Islands early Sunday, radio reported. One young person was killed in the attack
in the city of Gizo, according to a broadcast by New Zealand's National Radio.
The Australian Broadcasting Corp. quoted provincial Solomon Islands police as
saying 45 armed men, some apparently from neighboring Papua New Guinea, raided
the Gizo police station and telecommunications facilities.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Albright To Attend Assad Funeral
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NORTHFIELD, Minn. (AP) -- The White House announced Saturday that Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright would represent the United States at Syrian
President Hafez Assad's funeral. Spokesman Joe Lockhart confirmed that neither
President Clinton nor Vice President Al Gore would attend the service. ''I think
the president believes that Secretary Albright is the appropriate person to
attend,'' he said. He declined to say whether Clinton had been advised not to
make the trip.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Korean Summit Delayed One Day
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The first-ever meeting between South Korean
President Kim Dae-jung and North Korean leader Kim Jong Il, scheduled to begin
Monday, was delayed a day for ''unavoidable technical reasons,'' Kim's office
said in a news release. No further details were released. The three-day summit
caps six months of vigorous diplomacy with China, Italy, Australia, the United
States and other countries. The presence of 37,000 American troops in South
Korea and Pyongyang's nuclear and missile programs are among the most
contentious topics.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mrs. Clinton Can't Open Gap in NY
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Despite the departure of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani from the
closely watched U.S. Senate race in New York, Hillary Rodham Clinton has been
unable to open up a gap over the Republican opposition, according to three
independent polls. When Giuliani pulled out of the race on May 19, Republican
leaders predicted that by late summer or early fall their new candidate, Rep.
Rick Lazio, would be running even with the first lady. But on June 7, the
Quinnipiac University Polling Institute came out with its offering. It showed
Clinton and Lazio tied, at 44 percent each.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Northwest Offers Discount for Late Luggage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   EAGAN, Minn. (AP) -- Northwest Airlines will begin offering discounts on
future flights to passengers whose luggage doesn't arrive on time. Terry
Tripler, who follows the industry for 1travel.com, said the program is the only
one of its kind among the major airlines. The discount begins Thursday and will
be based on a sliding scale, starting at $25 and depending on the price of the
passenger's ticket, Northwest spokeswoman Mary Beth Schubert said Saturday. In
addition to the discount, a letter of apology from Northwest will be attached to
the handle of delayed luggage, she said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Homeless Man Bluffs Way Into Hospital
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- A homeless man carrying fake credentials bluffed his way
into a hospital emergency room and worked the night shift as a physician's
assistant before revealing he is HIV-positive, police said. The man, who
identified himself as Gary Lee Stearley, 26, was closely supervised throughout
the shift at Mercy Hospital and no patients were hurt, police said. He was
charged with trespassing and false impersonation and was being held Saturday in
lieu of $25,000 bail.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
