<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NJ fans erupt as Devils win 2nd Stanley Cup  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   After enduring five grueling overtimes in two
straight games,
New Jersey Devils fans went wild Saturday night when the Devils
beat the Dallas Stars, 2-1, to wrest the Stanley Cup from the
defending champions.
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Jersey won the best-of-seven series, 4-2. Game 6 was made
necessary when Dallas beat the Devils 1-0 in triple overtime
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh my God. Oh boy. Did you see that play?'' asked Dave
Belford, 32, of Toms River, who watched the game at Klee's bar in
Seaside Heights. ''It's about time. I couldn't take another third
overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Marino, 24, of Lodi, wedged into the Grasshopper bar in
Carlstadt near the Devils' home ice at the Meadowlands, along with
about 150 other die-hard fans.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm all emotional,'' he said. ''I tell myself I wasn't going
to cry and I cried. I was pulling my hair out the whole game. I'm
ecstatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans erupted when Jason Arnott scored a goal in the second
overtime, hugging each other, screaming, chanting and jumping up
and down.
</P>
<P>
   Marino brought his own Stanley Cup replica to the bar, made out
of a bucket and aluminum foil. He ate chicken wings from it during
the game.
</P>
<P>
   A waiter at a Paramus restaurant, he managed to get Saturday
night off to watch the game.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica Crawford, 44, of Newton, watched the championship at
the Grasshopper with her husband and three children.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a very long week - a lot of late nights. And I have
to get up at 4:30 and go to work,'' said Crawford, a nurse at Saint
Barnabas Medical Center in Livingston. ''I could have a very long
day tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, watching their favorite team was more important
than sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's fabulous. This is terrific. This is such an exciting
night,'' said the season ticket-holder.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second Stanley Cup victory for the Devils, the first
coming in 1995 against the Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   After the Devils won their first cup, more than 25,000 fans -
many in red and green body paint, horns, capes and pointed tails -
flooded the Meadowlands Arena parking lot for a victory celebration
several days later.
</P>
<P>
   There was no word early Sunday on plans for a celebration in New
Jersey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
