<DOCNO> APW20000611.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stanley Cup Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By IRA PODELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Martin Brodeur sat slumped in a chair, goalie pads
still on, puffing on a victory cigar in the small visitors'
dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   The two-time winner finally could relax after the New Jersey
Devils beat the Dallas Stars 2-1 in double overtime Saturday night,
snatching the prized trophy away from the defending champions.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an unbelievable feeling,'' said Brodeur, who made 30
saves in his 73rd consecutive playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur carried one of his sons, dressed in No. 30 jersey, into
the crammed dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's all over,'' the elder Brodeur said.
</P>
<P>
   It was during the triple-overtime loss that Brodeur's wife
Melanie was shown covering her eyes -- too afraid to watch -- and
then dejected when a sixth game was forced.
</P>
<P>
   She was in attendance again Saturday night and was mocked on the
Reunion Arena video screen by a female fan dressed in similar
attire and rubbing her eyes with a crying towel.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG GUNS: The Devils' quartet of Scott Gomez, John Madden,
Brian Rafalski and Colin White are now young champions in select
company.
</P>
<P>
   The group joined seven teams since 1927 that had at least four
rookies on championship squads.
</P>
<P>
   White, who still has rookie status, can do it again next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Montreal Canadiens did it last in 1986 when they had seven
rookies, including Devils forward Claude Lemieux and Dallas' Brian
Skrudland. Montreal also did it in 1971 with five and in 1956 with
four.
</P>
<P>
   The 1952 Detroit Red Wings won the cup with four, Toronto played
seven rookies in 1947 and Boston had five in 1939 and four a decade
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   FOR PETR: Top line forward Petr Sykora was injured in the
first period and was in the hospital when linemate Jason Arnott won
the Stanley Cup for the New Jersey Devils 8:20 into double
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's one of the hearts and souls of our line,'' Arnott said.
''We came into the dressing room and Patty (Patrik Elias) looked at
each other and said 'We've got to do this for Petr.' That goal was
definitely for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Derian Hatcher sent Sykora flying with a hit that the Devils
forward didn't see coming. He was wheeled off the ice with his head
and neck immobilized. A CT scan at the hospital was negative and he
was held overnight for observation.
</P>
<P>
   Elias wore Sykora's jersey while celebrating in the dressing
room and planned to go from the arena to the hospital, with the
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had real feelings when that happened to Petr,'' Elias said.
''I think every one of us wanted to win this for Petr.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   LINEUP: Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock made lineup changes for
Game 6, mostly necessitated by the inability of Jamie Langenbrunner
to play on his sore knee.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock had Blake Sloan in the lineup and scratched Roman
Lyashenko. Sloan did not play in Game 5 and the thought was that
his fresh legs could help the Stars to stave off elimination for
the second time.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner missed five games after hurting his knee in the
conference finals. He returned for Game 4 of this series against
the Devils, but could not go in the final two games.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Marshall, who was also in the lineup, Lyashenko, Sloan and
Aaron Gavey, all have had limited play in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Gavey, who was also scratched Saturday night, was tired in the
morning even though he didn't play in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd pay someone to take my skates off for me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   SUPERSTITIOUS STARS: The Stars' superstitions didn't pan out
in Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Keane's red sportcoat is now 13-1 in the playoffs and Ed
Belfour's lucky skates couldn't pull out another overtime win.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for Brenden Morrow to find a new way home. The
21-year-old forward has developed some quirks that he hopes will
pay off.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have little ones, nothing really strange,'' said Morrow, who
is dating the 18-year-old daughter of 41-year-old teammate Guy
Carbonneau. ''I drive to the rink one way, if we lose I won't drive
that way again. I'll take a different exit or something.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Keane's fashion statement, Morrow was amused at first.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought he was doing it just to get a laugh,'' he said. ''I
didn't know the record he had with it. I asked around as to what
was the deal with this red jacket and somebody filled me in.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   LARRY LEGEND: New Jersey coach Larry Robinson, who already has
six Stanley Cup rings as a star defenseman with Montreal and
another as a Devils assistant in 1995, made history with his eighth
title Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson took over for the fired Robbie Ftorek with eight
regular-season games left. He became just the third coach to win a
championship after taking over a team in midseason. He would join
Toronto's Dick Irvin (1932) and Montreal's Al MacNeil (1971).
</P>
<P>
   He also is the 14th coach to both play and coach a champion.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not about me,'' Robinson said. ''I am happy for those
guys that are out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 0233 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000611.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Derailed train leaks hazardous chemicals  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) - Several homes were evacuated Saturday
night after a derailed train car began leaking a hazardous
chemical.
</P>
<P>
   No injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine of the Delaware &AMP; Hudson Railroad train's 82 cars
were derailed in the rural town of Harpursville, 16 miles east of
Bingahmton, said state police Sgt. Steven Meyer. Seventeen of those
29 contained hazardous materials.
</P>
<P>
   The derailment happened about 2:45 p.m. Saturday east of Route
79 in Harpursville, parallel to Route 7.
</P>
<P>
   A car carrying methyl chloride began leaking sometime after the
accident and before 9 p.m., when houses in a half-mile radius were
evacuated. The Broome County Hazardous Materials Response Unit was
working overnight to contain the spill.
</P>
<P>
   Methyl chloride is a colorless, flammable material that is toxic
in high concentrations.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the train's other cars were carrying sulfuric acid and
propane, Meyer said. Soil in the area was found to be contaminated
with nickel hydroxide, which is flammable and toxic as a dust or
fume.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were still investigating the cause of the accident.
The train was going 35 mph, the posted speed limit.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Sabol of Harpursville said the track was lifted on its side
and cars that were ''stacked, tipped and twisted.''
</P>
<P>
   D&AMP;H Railroad officials declined comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-11-00 1026 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000611.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Couple files suit after groom arrested in 1996 wedding  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PLAINFIELD, Conn. (AP) -A Plainfield couple is suing state
police and the owners of the restaurant where they held their
wedding reception, claiming their party was broken up after an
exaggerated report of a brawl.
</P>
<P>
   Walter and Silena Ford were celebrating their wedding at the
Countryside Chicken restaurant in North Stonington on Sept. 21,
1996 when state police arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The groom was pepper-sprayed, handcuffed and charged with breach
of peace and resisting arrest. A jury later acquitted him on all
charges.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit blames restaurant owners Anthony and Ann Selvedio
for ''falsely reporting a disturbance to the police as dangerous
when in fact there was no imminent danger'' and ''failing to inform
the police that the disturbance was over.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fords say a guest had become intoxicated and unruly but they
forced him to leave the party before police were called.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a beautiful wedding until they ruined it,'' said Silena
Ford, 25. ''We had a great time up until that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Police had said that Ford became belligerent and was swearing
loudly. Ford said he was upset and may have raised his voice, but
he never swore.
</P>
<P>
   A trial has been set for July 7 in New London Superior Court.
The lawsuit seeks $139,000 in damages for false arrest,
unreasonable and excessive force, unlawful detention, malicious
prosecution and harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been four years that I've been fighting this in court,''
Walter Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, adamant about his innocence, took the misdemeanor charges
to trial rather than settling for an $88 fine and a $300
contribution to a state police battered women's fund.
</P>
<P>
   ''They ruined my wedding, so why should we have to contribute
anything to the state police?'' said the 31-year-old father of two.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys representing now-retired state Trooper R. James Barnes
Jr., who is named in the lawsuit, and the Selvedios, whose
restaurant has since closed, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   If they win their civil case, the Fords say they plan another
reception and honeymoon to make up for what happened the first
time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-11-00 1118 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000611.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wanna bet? Wagering on sports a political tradition  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Texas Gov. George W. Bush and New Jersey Gov.
Christie Whitman have lots to discuss - there's that little matter
of whether Bush will consider Whitman as his vice presidential
candidate - but their last talk centered on seafood and barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   In advance of hockey's Stanley Cup championship, the two
Republicans agreed on the terms of a wager: If the Devils won the
best-of-seven series, Whitman and her family would get a Texas
barbecue. If the Stars won, Bush and family would get a New Jersey
seafood dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Early Sunday morning, the Devils won the cup, making a winner of
Whitman. But Whitman revealed last week that a Texas barbecue
wasn't her first choice.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I really wanted to do with George W. - but he wouldn't do
it with me - is offer him and the family a weekend at the beach
house in exchange for a weekend at Camp David for me and my
family,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who gets use of Camp David only if he wins the presidency,
felt ''that would be presumptuous,'' she added with a mischievous
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The beach house Whitman referred to is a gubernatorial perk
located at Island Beach State Park.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman wagered use of the beach house last year in a bet with
Colorado Gov. Bill Owens on the outcome of the New York Jets-Denver
Broncos NFL playoff game. The Broncos won, and so did Owens.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's got a weekend at the beach coming,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman won her 1995 bet with Michigan Gov. John Engler when the
Devils won their first Stanley Cup against the Detroit Red Wings.
When the National Governors Association met that summer in Vermont,
Engler kept his end of the bargain by trying on a bright red Devils
jersey with Engler's name - and the Stanley Cup patch - already
sewn in.
</P>
<P>
   Bets between governors have become a common link between sports
and politics.
</P>
<P>
   When the Stars beat the Buffalo Sabres for the 1999 Stanley Cup,
Bush won a bet with New York Gov. George Pataki - and, potentially,
a stomach ache. Under the terms of the wager, Pataki owed Bush 100
of Buffalo's hottest chicken wings, and a dozen of a city specialty
sandwich: roast beef with horseradish on salty rolls.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge lost a bet with Engler when
the Red Wings beat the Philadelphia Flyers for the Stanley Cup. To
pay off, Ridge had to don a Red Wings jersey and drive a Zamboni
machine on the ice before the Red Wings' opener the next season.
</P>
<P>
   After the St. Louis Rams became Super Bowl champions earlier
this year, Tennessee Gov. Don Sundquist made good on a bet by
sending Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan a basket packed with country
ham, Jack Daniel's Whisky, candy bars and other Tennessee products.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Shure, who was communications director for former New Jersey
Gov. Jim Florio, recalled that Florio tried to bet then-New York
Gov. Mario Cuomo on the outcome of the 1991 Super Bowl, which
pitted the Buffalo Bills against the New Jersey-based, but New
York-named, Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem,'' Shure said, ''was that Cuomo claimed both
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Thomas H. Kean, who preceded Florio in office, said his
best bet was with Roy Romer, then the governor of Colorado, on the
outcome of the Broncos-Giants Super Bowl in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ''I bet him a whole load of New Jersey seafood,'' Kean recalled.
''He bet me a steer. Of course the Giants won the Super Bowl, and
the next thing I knew the steer was making its way toward New
Jersey,'' stopping along the way to promote Colorado beef.
</P>
<P>
   Kean got letters from New Jersey animal-rights activists
horrified at the idea of slaughtering the new celebrity. After
meeting the animal at Giants Stadium - ''I thought it was a pretty
antsy beast: you know, it snorted at you'' - Kean named it Jersey
Giant and decided to find it a home.
</P>
<P>
   That turned out to be the Howell Living History Farm in
Hopewell, part of the Mercer County Park Commission. There, Jersey
Giant helped recreate farm life at the turn of the last century by
pulling plows, cultivators and wagons.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Watson, director of the farm, said Jersey Giant died in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ''He reached 11. That's pretty old for a steer,'' Watson said.
''Most of them were intended to become beef at the ripe old age of
9 months.''
</P>
<P>
   Kean insisted that, over his eight years in office, he never had
to pay off a bet.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I was governor, we didn't let New Jersey teams lose,'' he
said. ''Never!''
</P>
</TEXT>
