<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Koreas Summit Delayed by One Day  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL SHIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The summit this week between leaders
of North and South Korea has been delayed by one day at the North's
request, the Seoul government said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The first-ever inter-Korean summit was delayed for ''minor
technical reasons'' and was not in jeopardy, said Park June-young,
chief spokesman for President Kim Dae-jung.
</P>
<P>
   ''The chief executive believes that waiting for one extra day is
not a major issue since the two sides have waited over half a
century,'' Park June-young said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear why North Korea, which is exercising tight,
secretive control of summit procedure and publicity, requested the
delay.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea has a detailed itinerary for the summit, but at the
North's request won't disclose its contents. Also, South Korea
government officials say North Korea is extremely nervous about
possible negative media reports of the communist country during the
summit.
</P>
<P>
   Culture and Tourism Minister Park Jie-won said that North Korea
complained about South Korean media reports detailing President
Kim's itinerary in the North, but he was not sure whether that had
anything to do with the request for the delay.
</P>
<P>
   Kim's three-day summit with North Korean leader Kim Jong Il will
begin Tuesday in Pyongyang, according to the South Korean
government. The meeting offers hope for a gradual reconciliation on
the Korean peninsula after decades of bitter conflict.
</P>
<P>
   A 30-member southern advance team is in Pyongyang to help
prepare Kim Dae-jung's itinerary and press coverage. Both Koreas
have agreed not to disclose details of the summit itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   But South Korean media reported the itinerary in detail.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential spokesman said North Korea requested the delay
in a telephone message sent late Saturday night through Panmunjom,
a border village inside the Demilitarized Zone separating the two
Koreas.
</P>
<P>
   The two Korean leaders are expected to discuss the dispatch of
economic aid from the rich South to the impoverished North, as well
as the reunion of separated families.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most contentious issues that might be raised are the
37,000-strong U.S. military presence in South Korea, and North
Korea's missile and nuclear programs.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's agreement to host a summit is a notable compromise
because it previously disdained most attempts at dialogue by Seoul,
a government it considered illegitimate.
</P>
<P>
   The two countries agreed to a summit in 1994. But North Korean
leader Kim Il Sung died at age 82 only weeks before he was to meet
his South Korean counterpart, Kim Young-sam.
</P>
<P>
   His son and successor, Kim Jong Il, consolidated his power in
the years that followed.
</P>
<P>
   The peninsula was divided at the end of World War II in 1945
into the communist North and the pro-Western South. A heavily
militarized border separates the two countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 1213 </TRAILER>
