<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Travelers asked to help design Pa. Turnpike rest stops  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) - Travelers are getting a chance to
influence what amenities they will have along the Pennsylvania
Turnpike in future years - and even whether there should be more
places to enjoy them.
</P>
<P>
   The Turnpike Commission has been surveying travelers about what
they think of the current setup, and changes they would like made
in a few years as the rest stops are upgraded.
</P>
<P>
   Now travelers who haven't been contacted can contribute their
opinions by logging onto the turnpike Web site and filling out a
23-question survey.
</P>
<P>
   They will be asked whether the service plazas should include
such comforts as showers, hotel accommodations, Internet access,
auto service and repair, or more dining options.
</P>
<P>
   ''As we look to the future, turnpike service plazas must meet
the needs and changing expectations of our customers,'' executive
director John T. Durbin said.
</P>
<P>
   The 507-mile turnpike system now has 22 service plazas, all
along the 360-mile east-west main line or the 110-mile Northeast
Extension. The rest stop plazas, open 24 hours a day, now offer
fuel, fast food and some restaurants, bank machines, public
telephones and other amenities.
</P>
<P>
   Every plaza used to be a Howard Johnson's, but beginning in 1987
they were transformed into a mix of franchises including Burger
King, McDonald's, Bob's Big Boy, Roy Rogers and Sbarro.
</P>
<P>
   Field surveys were conducted in February that targeted truckers,
business travelers, commuters and leisure travelers, and officials
are now seeking input over the Internet. The next field survey to
be done in August will have more detailed questions, spokesman Carl
DeFebo said.
</P>
<P>
   The current survey asks travelers how often they use the plazas
and when, and what services they use and to rank in importance the
available services.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on the subject of food, travelers are asked to rate
their interest in such things as 24-hour drive-through windows,
cafeteria-style restaurants, family-style restaurants, food courts
and 24-hour breakfast service.
</P>
<P>
   The turnpike commission also asks travelers how likely they
would be to use services such as showers, hotels, business services
such as fax and copying machines, or expanded tourist information.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the results, travelers should see changes over the next
three to five years. The planning process is tied to contracts with
turnpike concessionaires that expire between 2004 and 2009.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to have to know well in advance of those dates how
we're going to proceed,'' DeFebo said.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the response, the turnpike may consider things it
has rejected in the past, such as hotels, and may add more plazas.
The turnpike closed four plazas in the 1980s, at Mechanicsburg,
Denver, Path Valley by the Tuscarora Tunnel and Pleasant Valley
between the Pittsburgh and Irwin interchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Mechanicsburg plaza closed, westbound patrons have had
to travel 56.3 miles to another plaza. The survey asks customers
what they think the driving distances should be between plazas and
where new ones should be located.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will look at what users want to see in the service plazas,
compare those desires to what is currently available, and recommend
changes where needed,'' Gregg Schwotzer, president of Crossgates
Inc. of McMurray, said in December.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will also carefully evaluate the condition and location of
every service plaza and assess what should be done to make sure the
facilities reach their full potential,'' said Schwotzer, project
director for the consortium.
</P>
<P>
   Once the surveys are completed, a consortium of companies known
as ''The Turnpike Planning Consultants'' will do a marketing
analysis, and recommendations should be ready late next year.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.paturnpike.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-11-00 1225 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
