<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Koreans Travel North for Summit  </HEADLINE>
By SANG-HUN CHOE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Eager for economic opportunities, some
of South Korea's richest men will travel with President Kim
Dae-jung to his summit this week with North Korean leader Kim Jong
Il. But once they get there, displaying their wealth is off-limits.
</P>
<P>
   ''Please don't flash your dollars to the North Korean guides.
That will displease them more than anything else,'' Suh Young-kyo,
a Seoul government official, told the businessmen and other members
of President Kim's entourage last week.
</P>
<P>
   Suh was listing the dos and don'ts in North Korea for a
130-member South Korea entourage that will go to the North Korean
capital of Pyongyang for the three-day summit, which begins
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The first-ever inter-Korean summit was delayed a day for ''minor
technical reasons'' and not in jeopardy, Park June-young, chief
spokesman for President Kim Dae-jung, said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A 30-member southern advance team is in Pyongyang to help
prepare President Kim's itinerary and press coverage. Fifty South
Korean journalists will attend the first meeting between leaders of
the Koreas.
</P>
<P>
   The makeup of the entourage speaks volumes about what South
Korea's Kim seeks at the summit. He will take with him many top
industrialists and leading proponents of engagement with the
communist North, but few military officials.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of the 24 non-governmental delegates are
businessmen. Most of Kim's key economic aides and ministers are on
the list. A senior national security adviser accompanies Kim, but
the defense minister is not on the list. A brigadier general is the
highest-ranking representative of the South Korean military.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's ultimate goal is to end half a century of Cold War
animosities and eventually bring about reunification.
</P>
<P>
   Kim's best card is South Korea's economic might. Kim hopes that
impoverished North Korea will agree to a gradual process of
openness in return for investment and economic exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean delegates will tread carefully for fear of
injuring North Korea's fierce pride.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's OK to say thank you to North Koreans, but never pat them
on their back. They may take it as an insult,'' Suh lectured.
''Don't make jokes. And never carry any book or magazine that
criticizes North Korea. That could disrupt the atmosphere for the
summit.''
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's four largest conglomerates -- Hyundai, Samsung, LG
and SK -- are sending their chairman or vice chairman. All want to
expand operations in the North, where labor is cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the businessmen, Chang Chi-hyuk and Kang Sung-mo, have
more than money at stake.
</P>
<P>
   They are among millions of family members hoping for a reunion
with relatives separated by the Korean War that ended in 1953
without a peace treaty. Reunions will be a summit topic.
</P>
<P>
   Delegate Chung Mong-joon, son of the founder of the Hyundai
conglomerate, heads South Korea's football association and hopes to
persuade North Korea to host a couple of games of the 2002 World
Cup soccer tournament. South Korea and Japan are co-hosting the
event.
</P>
<P>
   Another member of the entourage is South Korean First Lady Lee
Hee-ho, who is involved in charity work. She might not get to chat
with her counterpart because Kim Jong Il's wife, Kim Young Sook,
has never attended state functions.
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean group also includes two scholars, a playwright,
a newspaper president and maybe a couple of dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Woo Moo-jong, president of South Korea's National Canine
Association, said he has asked President Kim to take two Jin-do
dogs, which are indigenous to South Korea and a national symbol, as
a present to Kim Jong Il. It is not known whether the dogs will
make the trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 1226 </TRAILER>
