<HEADLINE> Fiji Indians Mull Future at Wedding  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE CORDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Kirti Hargovind's ceremonially decorated hands
were draped in fake gold on her wedding day Sunday. She was afraid
she'd be robbed if she wore her real jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Only 150 guests out of 600 originally invited to Hargovind's
wedding at a Hindu temple in the Fijian capital Suva showed up
because the families feared a large celebration would attract the
attention of angry Fijians who destroyed ethnic Indian-owned stores
on May 19.
</P>
<P>
   That was the day rebel George Speight launched his nationalist
coup and took Fiji's government hostage in a crisis now in its
fourth week.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted it to be bigger, but since the coup we have had to
keep a low profile,'' said bridegroom Prabal Arora, an ethnic
Indian. ''We had to streamline and keep it simple.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing making some guests feel safe was a road block
manned by heavily armed Fijian troops just 660 feet away from the
temple.
</P>
<P>
   The reception later at a local hotel was also cut short because
the guests had to return home before the dusk-to-dawn curfew
imposed by the country's new military rulers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will have another, bigger reception after the curfew is
lifted,'' Hargovind said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the restrictions, the couple looked happy and proud,
Arora in a gray suit and Hargovind in a red and white sari
decorated with gold embroidery.
</P>
<P>
   Both were wearing garlands of white petals and green leaves at
the traditional ceremony and Hargovind's hands and feet were
intricately decorated with Indian patterns painted in henna, a
plant-based dye.
</P>
<P>
   But while they celebrated with their guests, they also thought
of the people too scared to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some people have not turned up because they were too
frightened,'' said Hargovind's brother, Dilash.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the temple, guests were discussing the coup.
</P>
<P>
   Speight's rebels are still holding 31 government hostages in
parliament -- most of them ethnic Indians -- to demand a new
constitution stripping the Indians of the right to hold the office
of prime minister and boosting the powers of indigenous Fijians.
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday, Speight met with Ratu Josefa Iloilo, the man
suggested by influential tribal chiefs to become the next
president. Speight has also publicly endorsed him.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a very fruitful meeting, they covered a lot of
ground,'' Speight spokesman Joe Nata said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   By agreeing to Iloilo, Speight has made a concession, but only a
minor one since the office carries little political power. The
selection of a new government is more crucial and has been the
sticking point between Speight and Fiji's new military rulers ever
since talks on ending the crisis broke down more than a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Military leaders have already agreed to grant amnesty to Speight
and the gunmen who stormed parliament. The military also has
scrapped the 1997 constitution and ousted President Ratu Sir
Kamisese Mara -- moves that fulfilled two of Speight's demands.
</P>
<P>
   Speight's storming of parliament triggered an orgy of arson and
looting of Indian-owned stores in Suva and many Indians, who make
up 44 percent of Fiji's population, are now just waiting for
normality to return before they flee the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many poorer people, if they have the slightest chance, will
get out,'' said Anand Patel, a local dentist.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no future here for us. It took us 10 years to rebuild
after the last coup (in 1987). It will take 20 years to recover
this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Chauhan Lal, who runs a cafe close to a Suva school, agreed. His
business has suffered because schoolchildren who supply most of his
income have been given extended vacation until the crisis ends.
</P>
<P>
   But even amid Fiji's coup crisis, the bride and groom beamed
throughout the ceremony. The guests smiled and laughed while photos
were taken before sitting in the shade of a jacaranda tree to eat
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ''To me, it does not matter,'' Arora said. ''I have the right
wife. I am with the right people in the right place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 1250 </TRAILER>
