<DOCNO> APW20000611.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Host families keep elderly out of nursing homes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KILLINGWORTH, Conn. (AP) - At 74 years old, Mary Robinson is not
a typical adoptee. But in a program that helps elderly people
continue living in the community, she has found a new family.
</P>
<P>
   The program, funded by the state and administered by a New Haven
social service agency, seeks host families for seniors who need
care but not yet that of a nursing home. The host family receives a
monthly payment of $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''I like this very much,'' said Robinson, who moved in with the
family of Paul and Amy Thomas in March 1999. ''You're in with a
family and they're all very nice, every one of them. I love them
and they love me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sage Services of Connecticut administers the program with the
aid of a $25,000 state grant. Assistant Director Shahnaz Solati
said there are four clients living with host families but the
program is pushing for more.
</P>
<P>
   Before Robinson was ''adopted'' in March 1999, she would often
huddle alone in her room at a convalescent home, listening to
classical music. A retired legal secretary with no family of her
own, Robinson suffers from heart problems, osteoporosis and
Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the Thomases, she goes out to eat with the family,
visits relatives and accompanies Amy Thomas on errands. She even
lends a hand with the family's two children -Paul Jr., 8, and
Cayla, 13.
</P>
<P>
   ''If things don't seem to be going well, I'll come home and
she'll sit down and talk with me and tell me what a great mother I
am and that I do a good job,'' said Amy Thomas, who works part-time
as a nursing home aide. ''She boosts me back up again.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Thomas said that when Robinson first moved into the house,
she tended to spend most of her time in her room. She often wore a
downtrodden look, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, Robinson began to feel like a part of the family.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we go out somewhere and we're pulling in the driveway,
she'll say, 'This is our road,' '' Thomas said. ''Then she'll say,
'And there's our lovely home.' ''
</P>
<P>
   An aide comes to help Robinson shower in the morning. After the
kids have gone to school and Paul Sr. to work, she and Amy Thomas
have breakfast. Robinson, a deeply religious Roman Catholic, then
goes to her room to pray.
</P>
<P>
   During the day, she and Thomas may do some chores together.
Robinson eats supper with the family each night.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson ends her evening by giving a goodnight kiss to each
member of the family. Often when she gets into bed, Ashlee, the
family's small dog, is waiting for her.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said she cherishes the love she exchanges with the
family.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to be nice to everyone because people really want to
be nice to you,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
