<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bashar Ascension May Set Precedent  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA ABU-NASR
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Bashar Assad's imminent rise to the
presidency of Syria could turn an idea many Arab leaders have
nurtured for years into a precedent: grooming their sons to
establish ''republican dynasties'' to ensure that power remains in
the family after they're gone.
</P>
<P>
   The transition of power from father to son has gone smoothly in
Jordan, Morocco, Bahrain and Qatar -- all monarchies. Before
President Hafez Assad's death Saturday, the phenomenon had never
been tried in a republic.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Bashar, other presidential sons whose destinies
are being shaped by their fathers include Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein's sons, Odai, 36, and Qusai, 34; Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak's younger son Gamal, who is in his 30s; Yemeni President
Ahmed Ali Abdullah Saleh's son, Ahmed, 30; and Libyan leader
Moammar Gadhafi's sons Seif al-Islam and Al-Saadi, the head of his
country's football federation who also aspires to be Africa's
greatest soccer player.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's bizarre that in a whole series of countries that are
nominally republics there's an expectation that the leadership will
go from father to son,'' said William Quandt, a University of
Virginia professor who participated in the Egyptian-Israeli peace
talks in 1978. ''It shows how weak the political institutions are
in those countries and how personalized politics is.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Bashar's rise to power would be trouble-free is yet to
be seen. This largely depends on the response of Syria's political
and military establishments to a hereditary-style power transfer
and on whether another family member, his ambitious uncle Rifaat
who has been banished to France since staging a 1984 coup attempt
against Assad, would cause trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Bashar moved closer to succeeding his father Sunday as the
ruling Baath Party unanimously nominated him for president. Later
in the day, one of Syria's two vice presidents declared Bashar
commander of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are divided over whether Bashar's ascension to the
presidency would set a good example for the rest of the Arab world.
Of the 21 Arab states, 13 are republics with varying degrees of
popular participation. Free speech often is limited. Parliaments --
where they exist -- act mainly as a rubber-stamp for the leader.
Referendums are organized to produce overwhelming electoral
endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   ''The aim of making Bashar president is to guarantee the
continuity of President Assad's path, which has brought stability
to Syria for 30 years,'' said Sarkis Naoum, a columnist at
An-Nahar, Lebanon's most independent newspaper. ''Any change in the
political system at this stage will bring instability to the
region.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Ghassan Beshara, media director at the Washington-based
Middle East Report, said ''to simply inherit, simply move into the
position without any competition or any fair and free election is
quite unhealthy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The rest of the world is moving toward greater openness and
democracy. ... We're going against the norm,'' added Beshara, who
is of Palestinian origin.
</P>
<P>
   The elevation of presidential sons to the rank of heir-apparent
marks a change from the 1960s and 1970s when presidencies were
toppled by military officers. Assad, Saleh and Gadhafi came to
power in such coups. Mubarak was head of the air force before being
appointed vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon of ''republican dynasties'' began emerging in
Iraq in the 1980s. Soon after his son Odai graduated from college,
President Hussein appointed him head of the Olympic Committee, a
position equivalent to that of a minister's, head of the
Journalists' Syndicate and head of the Iraqi Writers' and Artists'
Union.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam then put his younger son, Qusai, in charge of the
Republican Guard, an elite army corps, and security and
intelligence agencies. Both sons are reportedly vying for their
father's job.
</P>
<P>
   Other contenders began to appear. Assad brought Bashar home from
Britain where he was studying to be an eye doctor to prepare him
for the presidency after his eldest son, Bassil, died in a car
crash 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak has recently named Gamal, an economist, as a member of
the general secretariat of his ruling National Democratic Party;
Gadhafi's sons have been assuming larger public roles, standing in
for their father at some public occasions; Saleh's son, Ahmed, is
an army colonel and has been a parliament member since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   If Bashar becomes president, he will join a number of younger
rulers who have come to power in the past few years -- Jordan's King
Abdullah II, 38; Morocco's King Mohammed VI, 36; Sheik Hamad bin
Isa Al Khalifa, 50, of Bahrain; and Sheik Hamad bin Khalifa Al
Thani of Qatar, 47.
</P>
<P>
   ''These people came to maturity in the 1980s and 1990s. They'll
be more in tune with the majority of the population and more in
tune with the world,'' said Rashid Khalidi, professor of Middle
East history at the University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Would a younger leadership translate into a more benign Middle
East?
</P>
<P>
   ''What that will mean in terms of democracy, liberalization and
the rule of law remains to be seen,'' said Khalidi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 1323 </TRAILER>
