<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Path to efficiency for hospitals fraught with peril  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL HILL
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. (AP) - Vassar Brothers and St. Francis are
not the first hospitals to find the road to affiliation loaded with
landmines.
</P>
<P>
   An innovative maneuver allowed the two Poughkeepsie hospitals to
combine some costly operations without fully merging. These types
of joint operating agreements can allow coupled Roman Catholic and
non-Catholic hospitals to avoid controversies over reproductive
services.
</P>
<P>
   It worked fine - until New York's attorney general filed an
anti-trust lawsuit against them. A federal judge ruled against the
hospitals' joint venture in April. They are now scrambling to find
a solution.
</P>
<P>
   The predicament shows how tricky it can be for hospitals to join
operations as a way to remain solvent - particularly when the
merger involves secular and religious hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem arises from the culture clash inherent in
merging Catholic hospitals - which prohibit abortions and some
other reproductive services - and secular institutions. Many
hospitals have instead turned to more limited ''virtual mergers''
as a way of saving money while retaining their identity.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Poughkeepsie case shows, those agreements can also be
judged imperfect.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a strange dynamic right now,'' said State Healthcare
Association President Daniel Sisto. ''Hospitals are caught between
the economic imperative ... and community pressures to keep
individual institutions alive as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals merged in large numbers in the '90's, many of them
citing a financial need. The advocacy group Catholics for a Free
Choice says there were 132 hospital mergers and acquisitions
involving Catholic and non-Catholic hospitals nationwide from 1994
through last September.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Miller, research director for the Washington D.C.-based
group, said the merger rate has slowed since 1998. But she said
population declines and weak economies in parts of New York have
continued to drive area mergers and alliances.
</P>
<P>
   This can cause controversy.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, plans to affiliate the secular Nathan Littauer in
Gloversville in the Mohawk Valley with nearby St. Mary's Catholic
hospital have raised concerns recently.
</P>
<P>
   Another notable case occurred in Kingston when two secular
hospitals proposed to merge with Benedictine Hospital. Community
activists were upset over the potential loss of abortions and
reproductive services at the secular hospitals. The plug was pulled
on that merger in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Merger talks between Vassar and St. Francis were abandoned in
the '80's. In 1992, the two hospitals sought permission to run some
operations jointly.
</P>
<P>
   State health officials in 1994 approved the hospitals' plan for
a joint venture that involved a cardiac catheterization program at
Vassar and other shared operations. The hospitals eventually began
jointly negotiating contracts with insurers, according to court
documents.
</P>
<P>
   That's where they ran into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Two HMOs complained to authorities. In 1998, then-state Attorney
General Dennis Vacco filed a federal anti-trust lawsuit, claiming
the hospitals' charges were about 40 percent above the regional
average.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge William Conner ruled for the state in
April, saying the hospitals ''effectively fixed prices for most
services by negotiating jointly.''
</P>
<P>
   Conner conceded his decision could cause enough economic
hardship that one of the hospitals could go under, ''which
ironically would result in the end of local competition and an
increase in prices.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Perhaps the state will consider such long-term effects of
rigid enforcement of anti-trust laws,'' Conner wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, officials with Vassar and St. Francis have been talking
to the staff of current attorney general Eliot Spitzer about a
solution.
</P>
<P>
   The hospitals declined commenting on the case. A source familiar
with the case who requested anonymity said a consent agreement that
would allow the hospitals to continue providing care without
violating the law was being negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Sisto said the ruling has had a chilling effect on affiliation
discussions between other hospitals in New York state and muddied
an already confusing set of statutes.
</P>
<P>
   David Marx, a Chicago lawyer who has structured other virtual
mergers, said the Poughkeepsie case is an exception and that
properly formed agreements do conform with anti-trust law. There
are many other virtual mergers that have worked out fine.
</P>
<P>
   In Buffalo, five Catholic hospitals entered into a joint
operating agreement in 1998. In Long Island, two Port Jefferson
hospitals - St. Charles and John T. Mather Memorial - divvy up
specializations and share some staff under a joint venture that is
several years old.
</P>
<P>
   No anti-trust problems have arisen in either area. And as for
solving the problems between allied Catholic and non-Catholic
hospitals, some creative solutions also have been found there.
</P>
<P>
   After its merger with St. Mary's Hospital of Rochester, Park
Ridge Hospital opened a new birthing center last year. The unit is
operated under Catholic directives. However, women wishing to
undergo sterilization can have the procedure performed in another
part of the hospital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-11-00 1329 </TRAILER>
