<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Female legislators want male pronouns out of constitution  </HEADLINE>
By HADLEY PAWLAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The New York state constitution challenges
the capability of women in government by only using male pronouns,
according to two female legislators who want to make document
gender neutral.
</P>
<P>
   In legislation introduced by Assemblywoman Sandra Galef,
D-Westchester, and Sen. Patricia McGee, R-Chautauqua, about 170
masculine references in the 46-page constitution would be feminized
or made gender neutral.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the first step, at least, for those women in
government who have to swear their allegiance to this document that
doesn't even include them,'' said Barbara Bartoletti of the state
chapter of the League of Women Voters.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Schulz, chairman of the We the People Foundation for
Constitutional Education, disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ''Frankly, this rises to the level of frivolity and fiction of
political correctness,'' Schulz said. ''It's a waste of time and
tax money.''
</P>
<P>
   To change the constitution, two separately elected state
Legislatures must adopt the proposed changes. The proposal must
then go before voters in a statewide referendum. Sponsors said they
expect the bill to pass in both houses and face voters as soon as
November 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Galef said the main cost associated with the bill, which has
male and females co-sponsors in both houses, is holding the
referendum. Beyond that, the normal printing costs of updating the
constitution will apply, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Today there are 36 female Assembly members and nine female
senators, making up 21 percent of the New York state legislature.
Since the first two women were elected to the body in 1919, 104
others have followed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the year 2000,'' Galef said. ''We've had three lieutenant
governors who are women, the head of the court system is a women
and one day we'll have a woman governor. It's time for us to change
with the times.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, 10 other states have proposed similar
changes to their constitutions.
</P>
<P>
   ''This issue is coming up more and more,'' said Kelly Anders of
the National Conference of State Legislatures. ''I'm not quite sure
why now is the time. Maybe just because more women continue to
enter public office.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Mary Donohue, who is referred to as ''he'' in the
constitution, says it is time to catch up with the strides women
have made.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's never been a major bone of contention with me - I
understand it's tradition - but times have changed and it's
important to support and show respect for what women have done,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''All this legislation does is eliminate another barrier,''
McGee said.
</P>
<P>
   But Schulz maintains that a gender-neutral constitution ''will
not change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The state constitution does not now prohibit or restrict women
from holding any jobs in government,'' he said, adding that making
the document's language neutral ''will not enhance anyone's
liberty, rights or freedoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman William Magnarelli, D-Onondaga and a co-sponsor of
the bill, said that changing pronouns could have an important
impact.
</P>
<P>
   ''Young men growing up, and especially young women who hold the
fate of this nation, will come up with a new perspective,''
Magnarelli said. ''My daughters will tell you it's very important.
It will say they're a part of the constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the changes proposed by McGee and Galef:
</P>
<P>
   - A phrase such as ''The lieutenant governor, he shall...''
would be changed to ''The lieutenant governor shall...''
</P>
<P>
   - The pronoun he or his would be replaced by a title. For
example, ''His pleasure...,'' would become ''The pleasure of the
chief judge....''
</P>
<P>
   - Words like ''fireman,'' ''workman'' and ''assemblyman'' would
be changed to ''firefighter,'' ''worker'' and ''Assembly member.''
</P>
<P>
   - Wherever appropriate, ''he'' would become ''he or she,'' and
''his'' would be changed to ''his or hers.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a no-brainer,'' said Bartoletti. ''This is constitutional
cleanup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
