<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cirque du Soleil topples the big-top tradition  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
Associated Press Writer
With AP Photos NYR108-109-110 June 7
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Invoke. Provoke. Evoke.
</P>
<P>
   That's the motto of the Cirque du Soleil, whose avant-garde
clowns and acrobats have toppled the cliche of the big-top circus.
</P>
<P>
   One performer pops up in the air above the Nevada desert,
barechested in a gyrating cube that's consumed by flames. Suddenly,
he rises above the fire - a phoenix captured on film.
</P>
<P>
   It's a scene from the most bold incarnation yet of the
Canadian-based circus - a new IMAX 3D film, the 38-minute ''Journey
of Man'', which shows the odyssey of life through a circus that has
moved from the tent to spectacular natural scenes around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The screen production mirrors the Cirque du Soleil, meaning
Circus of the Sun, founded in 1984 in Quebec. It now has more than
500 performers who offer artistic acrobatics that break the old
pattern of elephants, sawdust and peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   A trailblazer among the new ''boutique'' circus acts, Cirque
draws an upscale audience that pays as much as $100 a ticket for a
live show, its seven troupes playing everywhere from Las Vegas to
Asia and Europe. One of them even puts on a dragon-and-lion,
East-meets-West evening with a special VIP package including
champagne and appetizers.
</P>
<P>
   But the IMAX version is for both adults and kids, at the
democratic price of a movie ticket.
</P>
<P>
   It starts with a ''Big Bang,'' an explosion of light and sound
that represents birth, followed by an underwater spectacle of
synchronized swimmers shot in the Bahamas. In the theater, bubbles
seemingly float from the giant screen into the audience via the
special 3D glasses handed to each spectator.
</P>
<P>
   Although the film is narrated by British actor Ian McKellen,
''it works without narration, it works on an extremely visual
level,'' says producer and writer Peter Wagg. ''You don't have to
explain - the cave is a womb, the birth canal is coming through the
water. It's all symbolic imagery.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a boy tumbles through a redwood forest filled with birdlike
creatures whose fantastic aerial leaps on bungee cords are his
taste of freedom. He's accompanied by two clowns representing his
instincts, in a tug-of-war between fear and curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   ''The creatures of the forest are all around you, and you'll
hear them walking through the theater,'' says director Keith
Melton. ''You are literally a part of this movie, because you just
get sucked into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds simple. But it took somewhere between $10 million and $20
million - Melton won't divulge the exact figure - to engineer this
film teeming with sights and sounds. Producers enhanced and mixed
natural sounds with digital ones using synthesizers at a California
studio. ''We wanted to put surreal elements in the real world,''
says Melton.
</P>
<P>
   Even for two pros, it was a thrill.
</P>
<P>
   When Wagg and Melton first heard the soundtrack, ''we literally
held hands!'' says Wagg, laughing and grabbing Melton's hand again
as they sit for an interview at the Sony IMAX Theatre near Lincoln
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech effects serve a higher, human agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Vachon, who plays one of the two clowns guiding boy, says
the film shows viewers that boys are little human beings. ''Even if
they are very small ... they take initiatives,'' says Vachon, whose
wife, Josette Dechene, plays the other clown symbolizing the boy's
instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must never think that we are superior to kids,'' adds
Vachon, his face half made up for the clown mask as he sits in
jeans before the film's U.S. premiere at the theater.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the boy reaches manhood, discovering love in a 17th
century garden - a scene shot at a California estate where statues
of a man and a woman come to life on a lily pad, in a virtuosic,
gravity-defying dance. The cameras zero in on each muscle and fold
of their bare skin - and even the slight trembling that went with
the effort. The water was dyed black to produce a reflection, and
the lily pad was made rock solid.
</P>
<P>
   ''These performers are really doing what you're seeing. It's not
a special effect, it's not a cinematic trick,'' says Melton. ''That
is the core magic of Cirque.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not all pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Having discovered love, the protagonist is led astray by the
demon-like Stiltman, tempting him with wealth that leaves him
feeling empty amid marble splendor. ''There's no family, no love,
no life,'' says Melton.
</P>
<P>
   He's eventually saved by a vagabond girl who brings back the old
bowler hat he had given up for a golden one.
</P>
<P>
   The characters' final stop is Berlin's historic Brandenberg
Gate, which once marked the division of East and West, and is a
symbol of new beginnings.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, this story aimed at family audiences exudes a certain
pie-in-the-sky idealism.
</P>
<P>
   But ''there are not a lot of family-oriented films that
emphasize these really important values - and that don't make kids
turn off,'' says Melton.
</P>
<P>
   He says the show, which runs in New York through September and
is being shown at IMAX theaters worldwide, makes an emotional
journey that shows off ''the idea of the human spirit, of how
spectacular the potential of the human body and spirit is.''
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying the story is a teacher's guide for children taken
to see the film.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the ''mission statement'' of the Cirque:
''Invoke, provoke and evoke the imagination, the senses and the
emotions of people around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   And in this film - with the fiery scene over the Nevada desert
and a dream-sequence flight into the Grand Canyon - the circus
truly provokes nerves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-11-00 1344 </TRAILER>
