<HEADLINE> Chechens Attack Russian Positions  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- Rebel fighters attacked Russian military
positions in Chechnya more than 20 times overnight, including 11
assaults on federal installations in the capital, Grozny, officials
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The latest wave of attacks was one of the most intense yet, as
the rebels step up their activities across the breakaway republic
on Russia's southern border.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Interior Ministry's department for Chechnya,
rebels opened fire on at least 20 federal checkpoints. There were
no Russian fatalities, but one soldier was wounded in Gudermes when
rebels fired at a checkpoint on a bridge across the Sunzha River, a
ministry spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal troops detained 20 Chechen rebels in a special operation
in the southwestern village of Urus-Martan, the military command's
news center said Sunday. The troops seized six assault rifles,
three pistols, two grenades and a bomb during the operation
Saturday, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   In other operations, federal forces destroyed four rebel bases,
the spokesman said. Three assault rifles, a flame-thrower, five
grenade launchers and 34 hand grenades were seized. There was no
way to verify any of the reports.
</P>
<P>
   Russian authorities are now concentrating on seeking a long-term
political solution in Chechnya, President Vladimir Putin said in an
interview with the German newspaper Welt am Sonntag, published
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''With large-scale fighting over, efforts are now being
concentrated on the prevention of sabotage and finding and
eliminating gang leaders,'' Putin said. ''These activities will
continue until all sources of terrorism are eliminated.''
</P>
<P>
   Chechnya's rebel president, Aslan Maskhadov, wants Malaysia's
premier to help mediate negotiations on resolving the conflict,
Malaysia's Bernama news agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would be very grateful to the Malaysian prime minister,
Mahathir Mohamad, if he could bring Chechnya and Russia to start
the negotiating process,'' the agency quoted him as saying.
Maskhadov's statement was sent to the news agency through
Maskhadov's son, a student in Malaysia, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has said it will not negotiate with the rebels, calling
them terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian offensive against Chechnya, which began in late
September, has stalled for months in the rugged southern mountains.
The rebels have kept up ambushes and bombings in the northern
lowlands, steadily inflicting losses on Russian forces and sapping
troop morale.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians were driven out of Chechnya in a 1994-96 war. They
re-entered in September after Islamic militants based there seized
several villages in the neighboring Russian region of Dagestan, and
after about 300 people died in apartment bombings the government
blamed on Chechens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 1345 </TRAILER>
