<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Norway Envoy Dies in Yemen Shootout  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway (AP) -- A gunfight between Yemeni police and four
armed kidnappers left a Norweigian diplomat dead, just hours after
he and his young son were taken hostage in the Middle Eastern
country, Norway's Foreign Ministry said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Gudbrand Stuve, 44, was shot in the gunfight that erupted
Saturday after his four captors were stopped at a police
checkpoint, a ministry spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It turned into a shootout between the kidnappers and the
police, and Stuve was hit,'' spokesman Bjoern Berge said. ''He died
a short while later.'' Stuve's nine-year-old son was not injured.
</P>
<P>
   The ministry said there were unconfirmed reports that one of the
kidnappers was killed and the three others escaped.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Yemen, an impoverished country on the tip of the
Arabian peninsula, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Stuve and his son were kidnapped when they went to a repair shop
in Yemen's capital, San'a. Stuve's wife alerted police, and about
two hours later, police stopped the four kidnappers and their
hostages on the outskirts of the city, according to the Norwegian
foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Stuve, a veterinarian, had just a just completed a four-year
assignment as a diplomatic secretary at the Norwegian Embassy in
Lusaka, Zambia. He and his family were touring parts of Africa and
the Middle East by car before returning to Norway.
</P>
<P>
   The motive for the kidnapping was not immediately known.
</P>
<P>
   Large parts of Yemen are lawless, inhabited by tribes that often
kidnap foreigners or use firearms to settle scores with rivals or
express discontent with the government.
</P>
<P>
   Berge said Norway would do everything in its power to see the
kidnappers brought to justice
</P>
<P>
   ''I am shaken by this tragic incident,'' Foreign Minister
Thorbjoern Jagland was quoted as telling the Norwegian news agency
NTB.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
