<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Official Begins Belgrade Talks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The second-most powerful figure in
the Chinese Communist Party began a three-day visit to Belgrade on
Sunday, aiming to expand cooperation between Beijing and the Balkan
nation now isolated by the West.
</P>
<P>
   Li Peng, a former prime minister and now head of the Chinese
legislature, was greeted at Belgrade airport by a group of Yugoslav
officials, including a vice-premier, army commanders, the foreign
minister and the speakers of both parliamentary chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Li and a delegation of political and business leaders from
Beijing were expected to hold meetings with Yugoslav officials to
''broaden continuing cooperation, solidarity and mutual respect,''
Yugoslav state media said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am very happy to visit Yugoslavia. There is a tradition of
friendship between Yugoslavia and China which will be further
improved by this visit,'' Li said at the red-carpet welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Li was also expected to meet President Slobodan Milosevic, whose
policies have led Western countries to consider Yugoslavia a pariah
state. Yugoslavia is under Western sanctions for Milosevic's brutal
policies in the southern republic of Kosovo, for which he also has
been indicted by a U.N. war crimes tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   Li is to deliver a speech to the federal parliament Monday
before finishing the first stop in his European tour. Li is also
expected to visit Slovakia, Croatia, Slovenia, Azerbaijan and
Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   China and Russia are among the few countries that maintain close
ties with Milosevic's government after NATO's military intervention
in Kosovo last year.
</P>
<P>
   China opposed NATO's 78-day bombing campaign, during which the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade was accidentally hit, killing three
Chinese citizens and damaging U.S.-China relations. China,
meanwhile, reportedly granted Yugoslavia a $3 billion loan.
</P>
</TEXT>
