<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs Mourn Syrian Leader  </HEADLINE>
By MAUREEN JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   Israel viewed with trepidation Sunday a new power vacuum in the
Middle East, Arab states went into mourning, while Europeans and
Asians paid tributes -- many fulsome -- to Syria's dead president.
Britain welcomed the prospect of his son taking over.
</P>
<P>
   In many Arab states, flags flew at half-staff and leaders
declared official periods of mourning.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak devoted a special Cabinet
meeting Sunday to events in Syria, in part out of concern that
Syrian stability could be at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Assad, 69, died Saturday after 30 years in power. On Sunday,
Syria's ruling Baath Party gave its presidential nomination to
Assad's son Bashar Assad, a 34-year-old eye doctor, who was being
groomed for office.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's very impressive ... I think he would be very good news
for the Syrian people and very good news for the peace process,''
said British Foreign Office Minister Peter Hain in an interview
with Britain's GMTV. ''But that doesn't mean to say he would be a
pushover in the peace negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Assad was credited with bringing stability to Syria. He also
entered peace talks with Israel, and had joined the U.S.-led
coalition against longtime rival Iraq during the 1990-91 Gulf
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Peace talks broke down in January over a sliver of land by the
Sea of Galilee and the Golan Heights, which Israel captured from
Syria during the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak at a Cabinet meeting Sunday
declared that Assad's death meant ''the end of an era.''
</P>
<P>
   ''... We are standing before another Middle East that we will
have to study,'' he said, according to his office.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who spoke with President Clinton, Egypt's Mubarak and
Jordan's King Abudullah II on Saturday, had issued a carefully
worded official statement Saturday saying his government
''understands the sorrow of the Syrian people.''
</P>
<P>
   However, former Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir bluntly
denounced Assad, saying the Syrian leader's only real success was
maintaining power and stability, which he did ''through brutal,
merciless means.''
</P>
<P>
   ''While the death of a man after a long illness should never
provoke joy, neither can I say that the news makes me sad,'' Shamir
was quoted as saying in an interview with an Italian newspaper, La
Repubblica.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton on Saturday praised Assad for making ''a strategic
choice for peace'' at a 1991 conference in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had our differences, but I always respected him, '' Clinton
added.
</P>
<P>
   Tributes Sunday were less equivocal.
</P>
<P>
   Austrian President Thomas Klestil said Assad was totally
committed to peace, adding, ''I knew him as a great Arab statesman
and a warmhearted man full of humor.'' German President Gerhard
Schroeder said Assad was a key influence in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   In France, which is the former colonial ruler of Syria and which
seeks a central role in Middle East peacemaking, Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin said he felt ''great emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   China mourned a ''respected friend,'' and Japan said Assad's
death was ''more regrettable'' because of hopes for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Russian President Vladimir Putin lauded Assad as ''a
friend of our country.'' But it was unclear whether Putin would
interrupt a planned visit to Spain to attend the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II sent condolences to the people of Syria,
saying God could help them follow the way toward peace ''for the
good of all Syrians and all inhabitants of the region.''
</P>
<P>
   In Lebanon, where Syria has been an unquestioned power since its
soldiers moved in during the 1975-90 civil war, Prime Minister
Salim Hoss said Saturday Assad's death had ''struck Lebanon in the
heart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 1430 </TRAILER>
