<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Inspects Lebanon-Israel Border  </HEADLINE>
By RODEINA KENAAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   KFAR KILA, Lebanon (AP) -- Lebanon protested to the United
Nations on Sunday that the newly drawn frontier with Israel had
been misplaced.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese President Emile Lahoud sent a memorandum to U.N.
Secretary General Kofi Annan saying U.N. cartographers had rejected
''an existing and recognized border to establish in its place a
fictitious withdrawal line to be used as the basis for confirmation
of the Israeli pullout.''
</P>
<P>
   A copy of the memorandum was given to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. special envoy Terje Roed-Larsen, who has been discussing
the frontier with the Lebanese and Israeli governments, said the
cartographers were not trying to redraw the border, but to define
it according to the line fixed in 1923 by colonial France and
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, people on the Lebanese side of the fence threw stones
Sunday at an Israeli border post, but Israeli troops held their
fire. The soldiers, under orders to shoot only in self-defense,
have wounded at least three people in stoning incidents since
Israel troops withdrew from south Lebanon on May 24.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of people have arrived daily in the border village of
Kfar Kila to vent their anger at Israel and take a look at the
country they have never seen up close
</P>
<P>
   U.N. sources said on condition of anonymity that the border
surveying operation began its third full day of work Sunday,
picking up from where it left off Saturday about 15 miles east of
the Mediterranean coast. The operation stopped Sunday night at the
border village of Maroun al-Ras, and was to resume Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Slow progress in verifying the 140-mile border has pushed back
the deployment of U.N. peacekeepers in southern Lebanon, where
anti-Israeli guerrillas have been the only real authority since the
Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Annan instructed the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon,
or UNIFIL, to complete the verification urgently. Little was
achieved that day because Lebanese officials objected to the line
drawn by U.N. cartographers.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon said it would deploy its own military to the area only
after the 4,500-member UNIFIL verified that all Israeli troops were
gone.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's withdrawal ended an 18-year occupation of southern
Lebanon and almost daily battles with Lebanese guerrillas. The
occupation was aimed at protecting northern Israeli towns from
cross-border guerrilla raids.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 1626 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
