<HEADLINE> NJ parole chief's relationships under scrutiny  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) - Authorities are investigating if New
Jersey state parole board chairman Andrew Consovoy had any dealings
or relationships with underworld figures, according to a published
report.
</P>
<P>
   Consovoy was named to the chairman position in 1998 by Gov.
Christie Whitman. Consovoy has said he is friends with a man who in
the 1970s as a county correctional officer illegally helped an
inmate in Essex County Jail meet women on the outside and get pizza
and fast food.
</P>
<P>
   That man, Joseph ''Gus'' Ferrera, has told Consovoy he knows
people in the mob, The Record of Hackensack reported in Sunday's
editions.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities are questioning Consovoy's relationship with
Ferrera, according to the newspaper, which also reported
authorities are interested in Consovoy's relationship with Dennis
Steo. Steo spent 23 years in prison for two murders police
described as cold-blooded, gangland-style executions.
</P>
<P>
   Consovoy has said he knows Steo but says they aren't friends,
the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper cited unidentified law enforcement sources and
several people interviewed by investigators, reporting that
authorities are especially interested in Ferrera's role as a state
employee assigned to help inmates prepare for parole.
</P>
<P>
   Court records indicate Ferrera spent seven months in state
prison after getting caught helping the Essex County Jail inmate.
He had been sentenced to three years, but was paroled after seven
months, according to prison records. Before his parole was over,
Ferrera was hired by the state Department of Corrections as an
''ombudsman,'' according to state employment records. The
Department of Corrections is a separate agency from the Parole
Board.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrera now earns $73,000 a year working in the Passaic County
Jail, said Chris Carden, a corrections department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Consovoy last month told The Record he is close friends with
Ferrera, and recently attended his daughter's wedding, the
newspaper reported. He also told the newspaper he used Ferrera's
condo in Marco Island, Fla., this spring for vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Does he know people who are in (the mob)? Sure he does. But a
guy's your friend, a guy's your friend,'' the paper quoted him as
saying. ''If he's involved in organized crime, it's a surprise to
me. If he knows people in it, it wouldn't be a surprise to me. I
make no bones about my friendship with Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   But the newspaper also reported Consovoy said in an interview
last week he sees Ferrera only once every few months for lunch or
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The other relationship the newspaper said authorities are
interested in is between Consovoy and Steo, the man convicted of
the two murders.
</P>
<P>
   Steo was released in 1995 after serving 23 years of a life
sentence, according to Parole Board records. Steo was convicted for
gunning down his partner in a stolen car chop-shop operation. Nine
months later, he shot an elderly Philadelphia gambler and dumped
the body in a creek, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Consovoy told The Record he didn't remember meeting Steo at a
Trenton restaurant party thrown in honor of Consovoy's appointment
to chairman. But the newspaper cited unidentified guests in saying
Consovoy and Steo were at the party. And one guest told the
newspaper Consovoy recognized Steo, shook his hand and sat down
with him. The guest also told the newspaper he flinched with
discomfort to see the newly appointed chairman rubbing elbows with
Steo.
</P>
<P>
   ''Did I run into him? I don't recall it. He's no friend of
mine,'' Consovoy told The Record.
</P>
<P>
   It's not known if investigators are looking into the Trenton
party.
</P>
<P>
   No charges have been filed in the investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-11-00 1658 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000611.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
