<DOCNO> APW20000611.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Marks 1 Year in Kosovo  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE JAHN
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- For Kosovo's Albanians, they came as
saviors. Most Serbs saw them as the enemy. But both sides agree
that since NATO-led peacekeepers arrived one year ago, their
province has not been the same.
</P>
<P>
   For the Albanians, the entry of NATO-led peacekeepers on June
12, 1999, signaled a new beginning -- self-determination after
decades of Serb oppression; peace after more than a year of war
against a powerful enemy, and a chance for democracy and
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   For Serbs, NATO's arrival meant the end of Serbian control of
the cradle of their culture. It also meant the end of the good life
as a privileged minority with all the state jobs, and most other
perks.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the big guns are silent. Serb-led Yugoslav forces
are gone and the ethnic Albanian Kosovo Liberation Army has been
disbanded, officially at least.
</P>
<P>
   But small arms continue dealing out death in near daily killings
motivated by ethnic hatreds. Most Albanians are no longer targeted
because of their ethnicity. But Serbs now are, in a slew of revenge
killings and other crimes meant to make them pay for the earlier
crimes Serbs committed against them.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, a crowd killed three ethnic Albanians near the
divided northern city of Kosovska Mitrovica, but NATO spokesman
Maj. Jose Pardo de Santayana said he could not confirm reports that
the mob who attacked them spoke Serb.
</P>
<P>
   Across the province, whole villages are being rebuilt -- but only
those inhabited by ethnic Albanians. Although Serb communities
suffered little damage during the war, Serbs who did not flee
earlier are doing so now because of continued threats.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder that Serb and Albanian look back at NATO's arrival
differently.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are many wrong things that happened during this year,''
says Besa Kabashi, a 23-year-old Albanian. ''But the most important
thing is that the Serb forces are out of Kosovo once and forever,
and we have the NATO troops to protect us here.''
</P>
<P>
   To the north, on the Serb side of Kosovska Mitrovica, Rade Zivic
curses the day the first NATO peacekeeper trod on Kosovo's soil.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hated them before and I hate them now,'' says the
44-year-old laborer. ''I will live in fear as long as NATO is
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Few residents actually saw the first troops arrive on June 12,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Most Albanians unable to flee the province stayed in hiding,
after months of Serb rule. NATO bombing -- meant to get President
Slobodan Milosevic's forces out of Kosovo -- appeared instead to
encourage Serbs to crack down even harder on ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the battle for Kosovo lost, many Serbs fled ahead of
the peacekeepers. Others barricaded themselves in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mostly the streets were empty,'' recalls Maj. John Spiszer, of
the 2nd Battalion, 2nd Infantry Regiment, who was part of the first
wave to arrive from Macedonia. ''There was hardly anybody out
there. It was pretty desolate.''
</P>
<P>
   Spiszer, 38, of Diamond Bar, Calif., remembers the chaos that
met the growing number of NATO-led troops as they spread out across
the province -- the Americans to the East, the British in the
center, the Germans to the South, the French to the North and the
Italians in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was shooting; there was arson, there was just something
every night,'' he says. ''One of my most vivid memories -- just so
much burning every night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Maxharrajs have different memories -- reaching back to the
nightmare months during the NATO bombing that started March 24.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were standing there in front of the window, just waiting,
then we heard the first detonations,'' recalls Remzije Maxharraj,
serving steaming Turkish coffee. ''We had a surge of happiness -- we
thought it would last only three or four days.''
</P>
<P>
   Days stretched into weeks, then months. Remzije, 50, stayed
inside, along with her two children Edmond and Albana, fearful of
marauding Serbs. Her husband, Syla, ventured outside every few days
to gather necessities.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to flee to Macedonia were foiled. Three times they
reached the border -- only to be turned back by Macedonian guards.
Once, Serb border police separated their 20-year-old son and their
daughter, 22, and demanded $100 for their return.
</P>
<P>
   ''We paid,'' says Remzije. ''Happily.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more harrowing was a police raid on the apartment in late
May.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were wild. They were shouting over each other so you
couldn't make sense of what they were saying,'' recalls Syla, 56.
''They screamed at us, 'where are your weapons, where did you hide
your money?'''
</P>
<P>
   Then they separated Edmond.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said, where are you taking my Edi?'' Remzije says, her eyes
moist with memories. ''They said, 'We are taking him as a human
shield against NATO.' I said, 'take me and my husband; take the
car, take the apartment, but leave the kids alone.'''
</P>
<P>
   Edmond, 20, came home unharmed about five hours later. He had
been released following questioning, after a police officer who
lived in a neighboring apartment intervened. That same officer
showed up weeks later, as NATO troops moved toward Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was crying,'' recalls Edmond, eyes thoughtful behind
wire-rimmed glasses. ''He said, 'I have to go, there is no place
for us Serbs here anymore.' I thanked him one hundred times for
what he did for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmond's sister, Albana, saw the U.S. Apache helicopters
sweeping low over Pristina's airport. They were followed by
potbellied transport choppers.
</P>
<P>
   ''She screamed, 'come and see this, you won't believe it,'''
says Edmond. ''How can I describe the feeling -- unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, Syla, says it was ''like having a mountain on your
head for months that was suddenly removed.''
</P>
<P>
   Syla suffered a heart attack the next day. His wife accompanied
him to the hospital and saw a Pristina transformed, teeming with
uniformed men who were friends, not enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ''My heart leapt when I saw all those soldiers, in position and
ready to fight,'' she says. ''I realized the nightmare was over,
and my children were safe.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kosovo Albanians like the Maxharrajs, the euphoria that
accompanied NATO's arrival is history. The United Nations now runs
a province kept alive on foreign aid -- and foreign guns. Most
Kosovo Albanians continue to insist on independence, but the United
Nations considers their province part of Serbia, and there are no
international plans to change that.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Syla, a county judge, has hope.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every beginning is hard and the main thing is that Albanians
are free,'' he says. We want a democracy like in the United States.
Maybe I won't live to see the day, but my kids will.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is no future for Serbs like Dragan Kosanovic, who fled
ethnic warfare in Croatia in 1995 -- and is now thinking of running
again.
</P>
<P>
   ''As long as NATO is here there will be no chance for Serbs to
return to their homes,'' he says bitterly from Kosovska Mitrovica.
''There's no salvation for Serbs in Kosovo as long as the United
States leads the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 1702 </TRAILER>
