<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cheers for Clinton, shrugs for Lazio at Puerto Rican parade  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton danced to salsa music and
was wildly cheered at the Puerto Rican Day Parade Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It was a stark contrast to the hostile reception she received at
two of the city's other recent ethnic parades, the St. Patrick's
Day and Salute to Israel events.
</P>
<P>
   ''This parade just loves her,'' said state Assemblyman Roberto
Ramirez, D-Bronx, one of a phalanx of Hispanic elected officials to
march with the first lady, as Fifth Avenue echoed with deafening
cheers for her.
</P>
<P>
   Her opponent in the Senate race, Rep. Rick Lazio, eagerly shook
hands with revelers but got a mixed reception and a lot of ''Who's
that?'' from the pro-Clinton crowd. The first lady was even cheered
by a small group of spectators holding Lazio signs distributed by
his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Boos dominated as Lazio passed by, but the jeers appeared aimed
mostly at Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who walked with him. Lazio
replaced the mayor as the Republican candidate three weeks ago when
Giuliani dropped out of the race because he has prostate cancer.
Friction between minorities and the police and other local issues
have decreased the mayor's support among Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Also walking in the Republican group were former Bronx
congressman Herman Badillo, a political icon among New York Puerto
Ricans, and George P. Bush, son of Florida Gov. Jeb Bush and nephew
of Republican presidential hopeful George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   George P. Bush, whose mother is Mexican, was an honorary grand
marshal of the parade.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Lazio suddenly dropped to one knee, and camera
crews and photographers converged. But Lazio, who fell and split
his lip in a Memorial Day Parade, was only tying his shoe.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras whirred for Clinton when she broke into an impromptu
dance with Bronx Borough President Fernando Ferrer, shimmying her
shoulders and spinning around on Fifth Avenue to the beat of a
blaring salsa band.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted to do it all the way down the avenue but we couldn't
get the band to come,'' Clinton said, flushed from the 90-degree
heat and smiling broadly. ''Maybe next time - maybe we'll dance on
a float.''
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Clinton angered many Puerto Ricans by opposing
clemency for a group of political prisoners who had been involved
in terrorist activities related to Puerto Rican nationalism. She
announced her opposition without consulting Hispanic officials, and
it was widely portrayed as a misstep in the ethnic minefield of
local politics.
</P>
<P>
   But those who marched with her Sunday said her support for
ending the U.S. Navy bombing on the Puerto Rican island of Vieques
had made up for the clemency fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   ''People felt so passionately and strongly about the treatment
Vieques has been given for 60 years from the U.S. Navy that her
position on that almost healed the wound,'' said Bronx City
Councilman Adolfo Carrion.
</P>
<P>
   ''She has consulted, spoken to and worked with every one of the
Puerto Rican elected officials,'' said Ramirez. ''I believe she
will take to the U.S. Senate a clear and very strong message that
the Navy must leave Vieques.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said she supports ''a complete cessation of the bombing
and an immediate referendum that would permit the people of Vieques
to make that decision on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has voted twice to end the bombings. ''As long as we get
the agreement of the Joint Chiefs of Staff that there are no
security concerns, we should phase out all our bombing operations
on Vieques,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Navy uses Vieques for bombing target practice, and
President Clinton has agreed to order the Navy out by May 2003 if
the island's 9,400 residents vote in a referendum to expel it.
Until then, the Navy training continues with concrete-filled dummy
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Although the parade was dedicated to the memory of the late
Puerto Rican bandleader Tito Puente, Vieques was the theme most
revelers expressed on T-shirts and posters that read ''Paz para
Vieques,'' peace for Vieques.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-11-00 1740 </TRAILER>
