<DOCNO> APW20000611.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nazi Hunter: Assad Death a 'Relief'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- The death of Syrian President Hafez Assad could
help determine what happened to a Nazi war crimes suspect believed
to have lived in Syria, French Nazi hunter Serge Klarsfeld said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''From a moral standpoint ... I would say it is a relief to see
Assad's departure to another world and a possibility to know the
truth'' about Nazi war criminal suspect Alois Brunner, Klarsfeld
said on France Info radio.
</P>
<P>
   Assad, Syria's leader for 30 years, died Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A French court ruled in December that it would try Brunner in
absentia for allegedly deporting 250 Jewish children to Auschwitz,
where they died.
</P>
<P>
   Brunner, one of the world's most-wanted Nazi war criminals, is
believed to have lived for years in Syria. France requested his
extradition, but Assad said that, to his knowledge, Brunner was not
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Brunner's whereabouts have been a nagging issue in French-Syria
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Klarsfeld said that Assad's death ahead of Brunner's upcoming
trial could help determine if Brunner ''was still alive or in what
conditions he lived.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We will know the truth one day,'' said Klarsfeld, head of the
Association of Sons and Daughters of Deported Jews of France. ''The
Assad regime has been prejudicial from all moral standpoints.''
</P>
<P>
   Brunner served as a top aide to Adolf Eichmann, the overseer of
the Nazi death machine. He allegedly helped organize the
deportation and murder of at least 130,000 Jews from Germany,
Austria, France and Greece.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the German news weekly Bunte published an interview
with photographs of Brunner -- then alias Georg Fischer -- outside
his Syrian villa. Investigations since then have been unable to
determine if Brunner was still alive. If so, he would be in his
late 80s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 1743 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000611.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Salsa and politics - Puerto Ricans shake it up at annual parade  </HEADLINE>
By PAISLEY DODDS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Hundreds of thousands turned out Sunday for the
Puerto Rican Day Parade, swaying to the thumping sounds of salsa
and criticizing the U.S. Navy's use of Vieques Island as a bombing
range.
</P>
<P>
   The parade up Fifth Avenue had its usual crowd-pleasers:
sequin-clad marching bands, floats, salsa bands, celebrities and
gyrating dancers.
</P>
<P>
   But this year's celebration also took on a political tone with
organizers dedicating the event to Vieques and Pedro Albizu Campos,
a figure in Puerto Rico's separatist movement who urged islanders
to start an armed struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ''Libertad!'' shouted throngs of parade-goers on a steaming hot
afternoon. ''Vieques, si, Marinos no!'' they chanted.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Puerto Rico's pro-statehood New Progressive Party,
including Gov. Pedro Rossello, boycotted the parade because of the
Albizu dedication, but there was resounding unity over Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Signs that read ''Paz para Vieques'' or ''Peace for Vieques''
draped the police barricades. A mock U.S. navy vessel dragging an
effigy of Uncle Sam trailed a 45-foot banner that read ''No More
Bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   In April 1999, stray bombs killed civilian security guard David
Sanes on the range in Vieques Island, which the U.S. Navy has used
for combat training since the 1940s. The Navy resumed bombing last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all want the same thing for the people of Vieques'' said
Jose Guzman, 45, who left Puerto Rico 35 years ago. ''We want the
Marines off Vieques and we don't want more people to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of people leaped over the police barricades when they saw
Ruben Berrios, leader of the Puerto Rican Independence Party. Some
embraced him while others shook his hand.
</P>
<P>
   On May 4, federal agents detained Berrios and 215 others,
clearing them from the bombing range and other Navy land on
Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   ''I came to the parade to pay tribute to my heritage but this
year is also different,'' said Christian Fernandez, 27, as she
frantically waived her Puerto Rican flag and wiggled her hips. ''I
came to speak out against what is happening in Vieques.''
</P>
<P>
   While the parade was also dedicated to Albizu, Puerto Ricans
remain divided over whether the U.S. territory should become a
state, achieve independence or continue its current status that
allows its residents citizenship but prevents them from voting for
president.
</P>
<P>
   Albizu, a Harvard-educated lawyer and leader of the Puerto Rican
Nationalist Party, was jailed on charges of trying to overthrow the
U.S. government. In 1950 he was convicted of inciting his followers
to try to kill President Harry Truman during a failed attack in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He was pardoned in 1953, but was imprisoned again in 1954 after
four followers opened fire inside the U.S. House of
Representatives, wounding five lawmakers. He was released from
prison in 1964 and died in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   ''Albizu, who's that?'' asked Jessica Torres, 19. ''We came to
see Marc Anthony!'' The musician, however, was a no-show.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds screamed when actors Jimmy Smits and Rosie Perez waived
to them. Even bigger howls were heard when they saw boxer Felix
Trinidad waving to them from his convertible.
</P>
<P>
   Missing this year was Puerto Rico's mambo king, Tito Puente, who
died May 31.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really sad that he isn't here this year to celebrate,''
said Jaritza Rodriguez, 16. ''I grew up with his music. My whole
family did.''
</P>
<P>
   The parade has been a New York tradition since 1957.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-11-00 1743 </TRAILER>
