<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More than 500 swimmers compete in annual Chesapeake Bay swim  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KENT ISLAND, Md. (AP) - An aerospace engineer from New Jersey
and a former school teacher from Massachusetts drew the loudest
applause Sunday as hundreds of spectators gathered near the finish
line for the annual 4.4 mile swim across the Chesapeake Bay.
</P>
<P>
   So what did Sean Brennan and Jean Ludtke do that so pleased the
crowd? Brennan, 26, from Forked River, N.J., finished the race the
fastest. His time of one hour, 26 minutes and 42 seconds cut more
than nine minutes off his winning time from last year's swim.
</P>
<P>
   And Ludtke, the oldest of the 559 swimmers, was the last
competitor to emerge from the water, finishing in four hours, 15
minutes and 20 seconds. It was the second time the Hyannis Port,
Mass., woman competed in the annual March of Dimes benefit race
from Sandy Point State Park on the western side of the bay to
Hemingway's Beach on the eastern side.
</P>
<P>
   Ludtke, who turned 76 on Saturday, said Sunday's swim across the
Chesapeake will likely be her last.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan, who finished the last hundred yards of the race using a
combination of free style and butterfly strokes, crossed the finish
line with energy to spare.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel like a million bucks,'' he said. ''I couldn't ask for
better conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Susie Rabiah, 33, from Shaker Heights, Oh., finished first among
women with a time of one hour, 40 minutes and 43 seconds. It was
Rabiah's first bay swim.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first 45 minutes I just went with the flow,'' said Rabiah.
''Then I decided it was time to kick it.''
</P>
<P>
   The bay waters were relatively calm and, at 69 degrees, warm
when the first of two groups of swimmers entered the water shortly
before 10 a.m. Organizers set the swim schedule so swimmers would
encounter minimum tidal currents, race director Charles Nabit said.
</P>
<P>
   After noon the breeze picked up and the bay grew choppy,
producing less than perfect conditions for the slower swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was so turbulent,'' Ludtke said. ''It was rough. Near the
end, I kept thinking how tired I was.''
</P>
<P>
   The bay swim began 19 years ago with a solo crossing by Brian
Earley, 39, a former Annapolis resident who now lives in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will be a world class swimming event some day,'' said
Earley, who flew in from the west coast to participate in Sunday's
event. ''There's only one Chesapeake Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   Nabit said the event, which raised about $50,000 for the Central
Maryland and Eastern Shore March of Dimes, reached its cap of 600
swimmers in 24 hours when registration began Feb. 1 on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ''We keep it at 600 for safety reasons,'' he said. ''If we
didn't place a cap on it, we'd have 3,500 or more people. It's that
popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Nabit said swimmers came to this year's event from 40 states and
five foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 559 who actually began the course, 539 finished the
crossing. The others were pulled from the bay for fatigue and other
physical problems by volunteer boaters who accompanied the swimmers
across the bay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
