<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profiles of Key Figures in Syria  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Some prominent figures on the Syrian political scene:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   BASHAR ASSAD, 34: Second son of Hafez Assad expected to succeed
his father as Syrian president. Studied medicine at Damascus
University and received specialized training in ophthalmology in
Syria and Britain. Returned to Syria in 1994 -- year his elder
brother and president's heir apparent, Basil, died in a car crash --
and began to be groomed for leadership. Led campaign against
corruption, recently started being sent on foreign missions. Made
commander of armed forces Sunday and nominated for president by
ruling Baath Party.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ABDEL-HALIM KHADDAM, born in 1933: Syrian vice president since
1984 who fell out of favor and public view in past year,
re-emerging after President Hafez Assad's death to issue
proclamations paving the way for Bashar Assad to succeed his
father. One of the most visible Sunnis in Syrian politics, Khaddam
joined Baath party at 17. Was commerce minister when he sided with
Hafez Assad in internal Baath power struggle and named foreign
minister a week after Assad seized power in 1970. Khaddam had been
in charge of Lebanese affairs from 1970s until Bashar took it over
in mid-1990s. Fluent in English, once the public, international
face of the Syrian government.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   FAROUK AL-SHARAA, 59: Foreign minister since 1984. Sat down with
Israeli negotiators in December and January at talks aimed at
securing return of Israeli-annexed Golan Heights in exchange for
security guarantees, normal relations. Former executive with
state-run Syrian Arab Airlines and former ambassador to Rome.
Suffered heart attack in October; married with two children.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   GEN. HIKMAT AL-SHIHABI, 69: Sunni Muslim who sided with Assad in
1970 coup and was trusted adviser for decades after. Headed
military intelligence from 1971-74, then served as army chief of
staff until retiring in July 1998. Recently admitted to the
American University Hospital in Beirut, but no reason given. Media
reports suggested he and his sons were involved in corruption cases
and said he left Lebanon last week for Los Angeles, where his son,
Hazem, lives.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   BASIL ASSAD: Eldest son of President Assad who died at 31 in a
1994 car crash. In 1992, Basil, who trained as an engineer, emerged
as the expected successor to Assad. Syrian army major considered
his father's favorite child. Known for his equestrian skills and
hailed in Syria's state-run media as ''the Golden Knight.'' Posters
of Basil still abound in Syria, where propaganda glorifying him
since his death has given him an almost saint-like image.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   RIFAAT ASSAD, born 1937: Led the Defense Brigades his brother,
President Assad, used to crush Muslim Brotherhood uprising in 1982,
leveling large section of Hama town and reportedly killing at least
10,000 people. Attempted a coup in 1983 when Assad suffered a heart
attack. Forced into exile in 1984 though not formally stripped of
his vice presidency until 1998. Last year, Rifaat's supporters
reportedly were crushed in Latakia. Rifaat's son, Sawmar, runs
London-based satellite television station Arab News Network.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   GEN. MUSTAFA TLASS, 68: Longtime staunch ally of Hafez Assad.
Defense minister since 1972, one of the most visible members of
Syria's Sunni majority to serve in the Assad government. After
siding with Assad in several struggles within the Baath Party, he
was a key player in the 1970 coup that brought Assad to power.
Known for flowery rhetoric in speeches and poetry. Published books
of his photographs of roses he grew and named after people he
liked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 1759 </TRAILER>
