<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Violence Strikes Euro 2000 Again  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT MILLWARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROTTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- World Cup champion France made a
commanding start at the European Championships on Sunday, the
second straight day in which violence struck the showcase
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The French, bidding for a second European title, defeated
Denmark 3-0. Italy squandered many chances and needed a second-half
penalty kick to beat Turkey 2-1. And Netherlands downed the Czech
Republic 1-0 on a penalty kick with two minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   The Italy-Turkey game prompted a fight between rival fans
watching on a giant screen 125 miles away in Genk, Belgium. The
game itself was played without trouble in the Dutch city of Arnhem.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-nation tournament has been marked by violence on each of
its two days. Authorities detained 48 people in Brussels after
police used smoke bombs to disperse hundreds of rioting fans
following Belgium's opening victory Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Genk, a gritty mining town, has large immigrant community of
Turks and Italians.
</P>
<P>
   The violence broke out after fans tried to leave the stands and
take the field of Racing Genk Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Officials tried to hold them back, but rival fans began
fighting. Police intervened with nightsticks, and several people
were hurt although no serious injuries were immediately reported.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, police in riot gear fired smoke bombs hours after
the opening game in which Belgium beat Sweden 2-1. Officials denied
eyewitness accounts that tear gas was used on crowds near the
Grand' Place, the neo-classic central square.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police, around 100 masked hooligans managed to
mix with Belgian and Swedish fans.
</P>
<P>
   Brussels Mayor Francois-Xavier de Donnea said one vehicle was
vandalized. The prosecutor's office said two hooligans were being
held and one was charged. Police said about five people were
slightly injured.
</P>
<P>
   In Bruges, Belgium, the French showed why they are a strong
contender for the European crown, with Laurent Blanc, Thierry Henry
and substitute Sylvain Wiltord beating star goalie Peter Schmeichel
for goals.
</P>
<P>
   ''We needed to be very strong mentally to go through,'' French
coach Roger Lemerre said. ''Even if we are world champions we have
to begin again here.''
</P>
<P>
   In Arnhem, Netherlands, Filippo Inzaghi of Italy scored the
decisive penalty kick after being pushed down in the 70th minute.
Turkish fans responded to the referee's questionable call by
hurling debris on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey's Buruk Ocan and Italy's Antonio Conte exchanged goals
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ''From where I was sitting I think it was not a penalty,''
Turkish coach Mustafa Denizli said. ''After the penalty my team
lost concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   In Amsterdam, the Dutch pelted the goal with shots but needed a
penalty kick to end the outstanding run by the Czech Republic,
which went 10-0-0 during qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   The game was decided when Ronald de Boer had his shirt tugged in
the penalty area and twin brother Frank de Boer converted the kick.
</P>
<P>
   ''We escaped lucky here,'' Frank de Boer said. ''I've said it
often, you really need luck in a tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Germany plays Romania in Liege, Belgium, and Portugal
faces England in Eindhoven.
</P>
<P>
   Police are particularly wary of the several thousand English
fans heading to the team's opener. Police will have far-reaching
powers to deal with hooligans, and special holding facilities have
been set up in the Dutch cities of Amsterdam, Arnhem, Rotterdam and
Eindhoven.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 1805 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
