<HEADLINE> Turkey Arrests Would-Be Immigrants  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Police arrested 210 hungry would-be
immigrants when their ship stopped at a Turkish Mediterranean
village in search of food, the Anatolia news agency said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees, who were headed for Italy, had set sail from the
port city of Antalya, 370 miles south of the capital, Ankara. The
ship docked at the village of Kapikargin, 100 miles west of
Antalya, after running out of food.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear how long the immigrants had been at
sea or when the arrests occurred. The refugees included 95 Turks,
as well as Indians, Bangladeshis, Iraqis and Moroccans. The two
Turkish captains were also arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the immigrants escaped into the wooded hills near
Kapikargin, Anatolia said.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of immigrants from Asia, the Middle East and Africa
are caught each year in Turkey as they try to enter more prosperous
European Union countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
