<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Final Auction of Ceausescu Items  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) -- The Romanian government on Sunday held
its sixth and final public auction of memorabilia belonging to
former Communist dictator Nicolae Ceausescu. His remaining
possessions will go on sale on the Internet in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The first day of the auction at the Mausoleum, which once housed
the remains of Romania's top communist leaders, netted $15,800.
Previous auctions brought the government about $625,000, said one
of the organizers, Dan Pojoranu.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the items offered Sunday had been gifts to the former
leader by the Communist Party, trade unions or companies he visited
throughout the country. They included heavy pieces of furniture
with carved images of the wild animals Ceausescu loved to hunt.
</P>
<P>
   About half the 200 items offered Sunday were sold. A doll
fetched $58 -- 37 times its starting price of $1.50. A 1974 Hillman
Hunter car donated by the deposed Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi of
Iran sold to a foreigner for almost $4,800.
</P>
<P>
   The auctions have been held intermittently since August, and
have disposed of over 3,000 items to bidders from Western Europe,
the United States, Israel and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   After this sixth auction, memorabilia will continue to be
offered on the Internet, Podoreanu said.
</P>
<P>
   The government said it still had about 8,000 items belonging to
Ceausescu and his wife, Elena, who were executed in December 1989
during a violent anti-communist uprising.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://ceausescu.ines.ro
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
