<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice President Gore Hits N.Y. Media  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After a media-heavy kickoff in New York City,
Vice President Al Gore's ''progress and prosperity tour'' this week
will concentrate on the Pennsylvania and Ohio battlegrounds, aides
said.
</P>
<P>
   Together, those states offer 44 of the 270 electoral votes Gore
will need to defeat Republican presidential rival George W. Bush in
November. The most recent statewide polls suggested what amounts to
a dead heat in both states, with Bush just a whisper ahead in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will deliver a health care speech in Scranton, Penn., on
Wednesday then travel to Cincinnati on Thursday to promote his
argument that narrowly targeted tax cuts -- rather than the much
broader, bigger cuts proposed by Bush -- are the way to help
families that haven't shared in the nation's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The tour begins Tuesday with a speech -- described as a thematic
look at the big choices America faces if its prosperity is to
continue -- at 1 p.m. EDT at the New York Historical Society.
</P>
<P>
   Former Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin will accompany Gore for
the first half of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a way, it will remind people the economic success of the
last seven years is not an accident -- it's the result of things
that were smart and disciplined. And, hopefully, it will raise
questions about whether they want to trust the economy to someone
who doesn't necessarily have that kind of experience and
background,'' said Mark Fabiani, Gore's deputy campaign manager for
communications.
</P>
<P>
   New York, not considered a real battleground state since Gore is
presumed comfortably ahead there, was chosen because the vice
president hopes to gain big, national media coverage of this latest
effort to regenerate his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He is scheduled to spend hours on Tuesday speaking privately
with The New York Times editorial board and giving interviews to
all the major network news anchors and correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   After a weekend of planning discussions, Friday's schedule
remained up in the air but aides said Gore will campaign in the
mid-Atlantic region before taking the weekend off for Fathers' Day
and resuming his tour next week in the Midwest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
