<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stanley Cup Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By IRA PODELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- The New Jersey Devils know how to disappoint the
home fans -- theirs and those in enemy arenas.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils won their second Stanley Cup, defeating the defending
champion Dallas Stars 2-1 Saturday night in double overtime of Game
6. New Jersey won for a record-tying 10th time in 12 road playoff
games, compared to a 6-5 mark at home.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not surprised, but then I am,'' said Randy McKay, of the
Devils, who won three times at Dallas in the best-of-seven finals.
''We knew Dallas had an unbelievable home record (9-1 in the first
three rounds).
</P>
<P>
   ''To come in here and win all three games is a little
surprising.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey, which lost at home in Game 5 in triple overtime with
a chance to win the Cup, equaled the NHL mark for road playoff
wins, established by the Devils championship team in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ''This time around, I think I realize it a little bit more,''
said goalie Martin Brodeur, one of eight players who also won in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, who swept the Red Wings to win their first Cup, are
5-0 on the road in the finals. They are the sixth team to win three
road games in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ''To lose three at home was something that we never imagined
would happen,'' Stars forward Mike Modano said. ''That was real
tough. To come back and win Game 2 after being blown out and give
ourselves a chance to win our home games and get that home ice.
Letting it go like that is really tough.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EVEN UP: In the last two games of their series, the Devils and
Stars were tied for a remarkable 193 minutes and 32 seconds of the
final 194:41 -- spanning parts of 11 periods.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 5 Thursday night, the teams were scoreless until Modano
won it at 6:21 of triple overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Two nights later, Scott Niedermayer gave the Devils a 1-0 lead
5:18 in the second. But Mike Keane answered just 69 seconds later.
It remained 1-1 until Jason Arnott got the Cup-winner at 8:20 of
the second overtime.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the second time, and first in the modern
best-of-seven era, that consecutive games of the Stanley Cup finals
went multiple extra sessions. In 1931, Montreal and Chicago needed
two overtimes in Game 2 and three in the third game.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles and Montreal were the last teams to play consecutive
overtime games in the finals, when they played past regulation in
Games 2, 3 and 4 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   LATE-NIGHT NHL: Arnott's goal was the third to win the Cup
late at night in the last five years. Uwe Krupp scored a
triple-overtime goal in 1996 for the Colorado Avalanche and Brett
Hull's controversial goal in a third overtime gave the title to the
Stars last year.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   OUTSHOOTING STARS: The Devils outshot the Stars 45-31 in the
sixth and final game and held a 209-147 advantage in the series.
New Jersey had more shots than its opponent in 20 of 23 playoff
games, including each contest against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   TOP COMPETITION: Not only did the Devils have to knock off the
defending champs to capture the Stanley Cup, they had to go through
two other clubs that earned over 100 points in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey became the second team to beat three 100-point teams
in the playoffs by eliminating Northeast Division winner Toronto
(100) in the second round and Philadelphia (105), the Eastern
Conference's top seed in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, the Pacific Division champion, had 102 points.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone's gunning for you and it's a long grind,'' said Mike
Keane, who scored Dallas' lone goal Saturday night. ''If we would
have won, this would have been the most satisfying because we know
how hard it is. Once again we had a great chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1980 New York Islanders also defeated three 100-point clubs
en route to the first of their four straight Stanley Cups.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   POWER OUTAGE: Dallas converted only twice in 16 power plays
against New Jersey. In fact, the Stars allowed just as many
short-handed goals to the Devils -- including John Madden's
game-winner in Game 4 and Scott Niedermayer's tally in Game 6 that
made it 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils had the best penalty-killing unit in the playoffs,
killing off 62 of 67 short-handed opportunities (92.5 percent). The
five power-play goals yielded were the fewest by a finalist since
the playoffs went to four rounds for all teams in 1980.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 1901 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000611.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devils Return Home With Stanley Cup  </HEADLINE>
By NINA RIZZO
<TEXT>
<P>
   TETERBORO, N.J. (AP) -- The New Jersey Devils returned home as
champions Sunday, hoisting the Stanley Cup high above their heads
as they got off a plane that carried them home from an overtime
triumph in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Arnott held the cup aloft as about two dozen fans cheered
in heat and humidity as stifling as the Devils' defense.
</P>
<P>
   The temperature was in the mid-90s when the team's chartered jet
touched down at about 3:45 p.m. at Teterboro Airport, a small
airfield used by many business, entertainment and sports figures
seeking an alternative to huge commercial airports.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Postolwski, a computer artist from Mahwah, N.J., came with
a camera to get some snapshots.
</P>
<P>
   ''They showed a lot of heart to stick it in there when everyone
was writing them off,'' he said. ''It took a lot of guts and
courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen-year-old Kevin Makely of Hasbrouck Heights had a simple
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just want to touch the cup,'' he said. He didn't get to
touch it, but he stood and cheered at the exit of the Atlantic
Aviation terminal as the team's bus pulled out, en route to the
Continental Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a hard-fought series,'' said James Vera, 32. His aunt,
Sonia Fuentes, 57, of Hackensack, raised both fists and said, ''I'm
here to root the team on.''
</P>
<P>
   Christine Maita, a 26-year-old nurse from Little Ferry, brought
a Ken Daneyko jersey with her, but it was too hot to wear, so she
sat on it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd just like to see them and get an autograph, but I don't
think it will happen,'' Maita said.
</P>
<P>
   A few lucky fans who gathered outside the arena did manage to
get autographs as the players scampered off the team bus toward
their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Petr Sykora, who was hospitalized for observation Saturday night
after taking a blow to the head from Stars captain Derian Hatcher
in the first period, accompanied the team on the flight home, but
went straight to his car, still suffering from a headache.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, were glad to oblige the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ''Words can't describe it,'' Daneyko said of his feeling after
clinching the cup. ''This one was something special. The guys were
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It feels great,'' Arnott added. ''It's a dream come true.
Every player dreams about this. The last couple of years, we had
something to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   Devils general manager Lou Lamoriello said the team never lost
its poise. He also said the team's second Stanley Cup was harder to
get than the first one in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone says it's more difficult when you've never won it
before,'' he said. ''But in my mind, the second one is harder
because you're expected to win it. And then if you don't, they
suspect something's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is tremendous for hockey, and tremendous for the local
market and the fans. This was a special feat because we dethroned
last year's champions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 1902 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000611.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assad Death Could Destabilize Syria  </HEADLINE>
By BASSEM MROUE
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- President Hosni Mubarak devoted a special
Cabinet meeting Sunday to Syria, concerned that the fellow Arab
nation's stability could be at risk after the death of its leader,
Hafez Assad.
</P>
<P>
   Just one day after Assad's death at age 69, Syria's ruling Baath
Party unanimously nominated his son Bashar, a 34-year-old
ophthalmologist, for president. Assad had groomed Bashar for the
post.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are hearing that there is a candidate who is Dr. Bashar
Assad, and we wish him all the best,'' Mubarak told reporters after
the Cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Syria was the only subject of discussion at Sunday's meeting
''because (Assad's death) is a huge incident,'' he said. Assad
ruled Syria for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were shocked by the death of a colleague and a brother,''
Mubarak said. ''We hope from deep in our hearts that Syria will be
stable, and we will support the leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Expressions of sorrow and words of praise for Assad continued
Sunday from leaders and commentators in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Arab world analysts expected Bashar would become Syria's next
leader, though some expressed fears he would not ascend
unchallenged. Besides the uncertainty of his support among the
military, Bashar's uncle, Rifaat, attempted a coup against his
brother in 1984 and is thought to still harbor leadership
ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The struggle for power between the old guard and the new will
not be a picnic or a walk in the park. The price will be dear, very
dear. May God protect Syria and its people from all evil,''
columnist Fouad al-Hashem wrote in Sunday's edition of the Kuwaiti
daily Al-Watan.
</P>
<P>
   Assad's final months were dominated by efforts to secure the
return of the Golan Heights, which Israel seized in the 1967 Middle
East war. Talks had been stalled since January, but despite his
failing health, Assad wouldn't be pressured to bend.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Justice Minister Yossi Beilin said in Jerusalem that
Bashar Assad could smooth the way for a peace arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will be easier for a new generation that is not part of the
rejectionist camp to comply with the existence of Israel,'' said
Beilin, who described the elder Assad as an enemy of Israel
respected as the legitimate leader of a neighboring state.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak and his army commanders have said they
hope for stability. ''We hope the Syrian leadership will remain
stable and the situation will remain stable until a successor is
chosen,'' said Maj. Gen. Gabi Ashkenazi, who commands forces in
Israel's north.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli military officials said they expected the younger Assad
to maintain his father's policies, and noted reports that the elder
Assad had in recent months purged his regime of threats to Bashar's
succession.
</P>
<P>
   The Jordan Times, an Amman-based English-language newspaper,
said that whoever assumed the Syrian presidency would also have
domestic concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hafez Assad's successor will inherit a country with the
diseases that are almost typical in this region: Corruption, a
struggling economy in need of modernization and liberalization, and
the challenges of democratization lying ahead,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed al-Jarrallah, editor in chief of another Kuwait daily
Al-Siyassah, suggested Bashar was ready for such challenges. Bashar
has been leading a campaign against corruption in Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Bashar ''is his father's son and a graduate of his school,'' he
wrote in a signed editorial Sunday. Bashar ''has the benefit of a
young mentality, the higher ability to modernize and the total
acceptance of the facts of the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
