<HEADLINE> Athletics 6, Dodgers 0  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Kevin Appier earned his 11th career shutout,
ending a drought of 36 starts without a complete game, and Miguel
Tejada highlighted a five-run first inning with a two-run double as
the Oakland Athletics beat the Los Angeles Dodgers 6-0 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Appier (6-3) scattered seven hits, struck out six and walked one
while improving his road record to 5-0. The shutout was his first
in 75 starts since May 5, 1997, when he pitched Kansas City to a
2-0 victory at Boston with a five-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old right-hander was staked to a 5-0 lead before
throwing his first pitch ever against the Dodgers. He also got his
first major league hit, a fourth-inning single.
</P>
<P>
   Appier's complete-game shutout was the first by an Oakland
pitcher since Sept. 4, 1998 when Kenny Rogers beat Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Eric Gagne (1-4) failed to retire any of the first five
batters while loading the bases with consecutive walks. Terrence
Long, who opened the game with a single, scored when Gagne grazed
cleanup hitter Matt Stairs above the right elbow with a 2-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Tejada made it 3-0 with a double to right-center and Eric Chavez
capped the rally with a two-out, two-run single that extended his
hitting streak to 10 games -- the longest of his career and the
longest of any Oakland batter this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics, who have won nine of 11, scored their sixth run
on a double steal in the fifth. Jason Giambi led off with a double,
then beat the throw to third from catcher Paul LoDuca on a short
wild pitch to the right of the plate with two out. Ben Grieve was
intentionally walked, then broke for second as Giambi beat the
return throw home from second baseman Mark Grudzielanek.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne was charged with six runs and six hits in five innings,
striking out six and walking four.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Dodgers will reach the one-million mark in home
attendance on Monday night when they host the NL West-leading
Arizona Diamondbacks in the opener of a four-game series. ...
Appier had pitched only one other complete game in the last three
seasons, a three-hit, 7-1 victory on May 12, 1999, for the Royals
against Toronto. All three hits in that game were by current Dodger
Shawn Green, who had a first-inning double on Sunday. ... Giambi
drew three walks, increasing his AL-leading total to 53. He had 105
bases on balls last season. ... Appier has received at least six
runs of support in six of his 11 starts this season.
</P>
