<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High temps near record in N.J.; storm on way  </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Temperatures approached record highs in
much of New Jersey Sunday as the state braced for severe
thunderstorms that were poised to cool things down.
</P>
<P>
   The mercury reached 95 degrees in Newark, and was at 92 in
Teterboro as of 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   State environmental authorities issued an air pollution advisory
warning of unhealthy air over most of the state. And a series of
severe thunderstorms was forecast for northern and coastal New
Jersey for later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen die-hard New Jersey Devils fans braved scorching
temperatures and stifling humidity to turn out at Teterboro
Airport, where the team's chartered jet was to land after the team
won the Stanley Cup early Sunday in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just want to touch the cup,'' said 18-year-old Kevin Makely
of Hasbrouck Heights.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Olympic rowing team trials were held earlier than
scheduled Sunday because of the heat, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The heat caused a drawbridge over the Manasquan River in Brielle
to expand, preventing it from closing, a police dispatcher said.
The bridge, on Route 70, was stuck open for almost two hours,
causing a traffic nightmare for beachgoers leaving the Shore.
Workers managed to get the bridge closed just before 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Environmental Protection said concentrations
of ozone had reached unhealthy levels in Camden and Gloucester
counties, and was approaching that level in Ocean County. Such
levels can cause coughing, chest pains, decreased lung function,
shortness of breath, and can aggravate asthma and other respiratory
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Children, senior citizens and those with existing respiratory
diseases are considered the most at risk.
</P>
<P>
   State officials also said air quality in northeastern and
southerwestern New Jersey were poor because of high levels of fine
particulates.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service issued an excessive heat warning
for urban areas. And it also issued a severe thunderstorm watch for
northern New Jersey and coastal areas from 2:15 p.m. to 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Two-inch hail, dangerous lightning and wind gusts of up to 70
m.p.h. were forecast. Winds are considered hurricane-force when
they reach 74 m.p.h.
</P>
<P>
   Once the storms pass, Monday's high temperatures are expected to
be around 80 in much of the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-11-00 1931 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
