<HEADLINE> 8 Crews Earn Olympic Berths  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- Don Smith and Aquil Abdullah will face off
once again Monday to complete the U.S. Rowing Olympic team. Eight
of the nine crews for Olympic team were selected Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The second-seeded Smith finished in 6:57.96 to edge the
top-seeded Abdullah by 3.75 seconds. Abdullah won the first final,
but suffered an asthma attack on Sunday, forcing a third final. The
winner of that race will go to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   In the women's single sculls, top-seeded Monica Tranel-Michini
clocked a 7:35.23 to finish 5.11 seconds ahead of second-place Lisa
Schlenker.
</P>
<P>
   Tranel-Michini, a 1996 Olympian in the women's eight, will
travel to the European Olympic Qualifying Regatta in Lucerne,
Switzerland, in July to qualify the boat for the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Tucker and Conal Groom, the top seeds in the men's
lightweight double sculls, won a close race by 1.48 seconds. Tucker
and Groom clocked a 6:13.86 to best Bill Belden and Greg Ruckman.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker and Groom finished sixth at the 1999 World Championships
and qualified the boat for the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   In the women's double sculls, Ruth Davidon and Carol Skricki won
in 6:56.04, beating Leslie Rawley and Kate MacKenzie by 2.52
seconds. Davidon and Skricki will travel to Lucerne to qualify the
boat.
</P>
<P>
   Top seeds Mike Ferry and Henry Nuzum won the second final of the
men's double sculls in 6:12.09, edging David Gleeson and Chris
Duffy by 3.18 seconds. The United States already has qualified for
the Games in the double, so Ferry and Nuzum will go to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   In the women's lightweight double sculls, Sarah Garner and
Christine Collins won in 6:50.58. Angie Cummins and Whitney Post
finished second in 6:53.94. Garner and Collins, the 1999 world
silver medalists in the event, have already qualified their boat
for the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Kraft and Missy Ryan, 1996 Olympic silver medalists in the
event, captured the second final of the women's pair. Their 6:59.57
was good for a 6.99-second victory over Lianne Nelson and Katie
Maloney.
</P>
<P>
   On the men's side, No. 1 seeds Ted Murphy and Sebastian Bea
finished in 6:18.02 in the closest race of the day. A photo finish
showed a 0.23-second edge over second-place finishers Thomas Bohrer
and Adam Holland. Murphy and Bea will travel to Lucerne to attempt
to qualify the boat for the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   In the men's quadruple sculls, Nick Peterson, Ian McGowan, Jake
Wetzel and Sean Hall of the Augusta Training Center finished in
5:42.83 -- 4.96 seconds ahead of the Princeton Training Center boat.
The Augusta boat will travel to Lucerne to attempt to qualify for
the Games.
</P>
