<HEADLINE> Pacers Lead Lakers 23-15 After 1Q  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- A boisterous home crowd and hot shooting
from Indiana's stars helped the Pacers take a 23-15 lead over the
Los Angeles Lakers after the first quarter in Game 3 of the NBA
Finals on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant's sprained left ankle kept him out of the Lakers'
lineup, and Reggie Miller capitalized by scoring seven points.
Jalen Rose had eight points on 4-of-5 shooting, most during a 15-4
run midway through the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles won the first two games of the series at Staples
Center. Sunday's game was the first home Finals game ever played by
the Pacers, who won three championships in the ABA.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers lacked patience on offense, settling for jumpers
instead of working the ball into Shaquille O'Neal. The league MVP,
who averaged 41.5 points and 21.5 rebounds in the first two games
of the Finals, got just one shot in the game's first 11 minutes and
had five points at quarter's end.
</P>
<P>
   Heeding coach Larry Bird's directive, Indiana got the ball
inside to center Rik Smits in an effort to draw fouls on O'Neal.
But Smits took mostly outside shots and went 3-for-9 from the
field, keeping Indiana's lead small.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jackson scored the game's first basket and made the sign of
the cross, which he began doing during the Eastern Conference
finals against New York. The Conseco Fieldhouse crowd loved it, and
they also booed O'Neal at every opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Davis had six rebounds in the first quarter for the Pacers.
Los Angeles made seven turnovers in the period.
</P>
<P>
   The players were much more feisty than in the first two games,
with Davis and the Lakers' Robert Horry exchanging stares and
shoves after Horry threw the ball hard at Davis while falling out
of bounds. Dual technicals were called on Jackson and Ron Harper
when the two shoved the ball at each other with 2:34 to play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 2016 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
