<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quinn Wins Lemieux Invitational  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEIDELBERG, Pa. (AP) -- Dan Quinn birdied three of the final six
holes for a final-round 69, winning the Mario Lemieux Celebrity
Invitational golf tournament Sunday with a 14-under-par 202 total,
best-ever on the Celebrity Players Tour.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-year NHL veteran, who played with Lemieux in Pittsburgh,
entered the final round with a double-digit lead, but almost took
himself out of action when he walked into the nearby scoreboard on
the seventh hole.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mario pushed me -- he tried to win,'' Quinn said with a grin.
''He just pushed me right into the scoreboard. I was being a
showoff and saying ''Hi'' to the kids, and wasn't paying
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I hit hard,'' Quinn said. ''Somebody said that was harder than
I ever got hit in hockey, and I didn't like that.''
</P>
<P>
   After parring that hole and shooting a 35 on the front nine,
Quinn added a 34 on the back to win by 14 strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn, who finished third last year, donated half of the $40,000
first prize to the Lemieux Foundation for cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   ''I played really well,'' Quinn said. ''I just had one bogey on
12, and I think I hit every green except 12. Mario said I didn't
play this well the past few years, but I haven't played this well
in 35 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ''(Quinn) hit so many good shots the last two days that I played
with him and only two bad drives, so he played some unbelievable
golf,'' Lemieux said.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Titans placekicker Al Del Greco (69) and former major
league left-hander Shane Rawley (70) tied for second at even-par
216, earning $21,000 each. Del Greco eagled No. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Former tennis star Ivan Lendl, second going into the final
round, finished fourth (76--219), while former NFL quarterback Mark
Rypien moved up to fifth (73--220). Former St. Louis Cardinals
outfielder Andy Van Slyke (75) and San Francisco 49ers quarterback
John Brodie (76) were tied for sixth at 222.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux (81) tied for 10th with another former Penguins player,
Pierre Larouche (72), at 225.
</P>
<P>
   Two-time defending Lemieux Invitational champion Rick Rhoden
(79) was 12th overall with a 10-over 226. Last year's runner-up,
former Denver Broncos quarterback John Elway, tied for 23rd
(78--233).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 2017 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000611.0118 </DOCNO>
