<HEADLINE> Sunday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
B.C. Gov't Funds Stripper Study
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- The University of British
Columbia wants former strippers to bare it all -- for research.
</P>
<P>
   A three-year study, funded by the federal government, will look
into the history of erotic entertainment in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   From pasties to lap dances, Prof. Becki Ross is looking for
stories from the front lines of what she calls this ''little
understood, much maligned'' business.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see it as an art form,'' said Ross, who teaches sociology at
UBC. ''I actually am in awe of the women on the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver once claimed one of the hottest night spots north of
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Erotic pioneers like Josephine Baker, Lili St. Cyr and Gypsy
Rose Lee took the stage to take it all off in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Ross will receive about $50,000 from the federal Social Sciences
and Humanities Research Council of Canada over the next three years
for her research.
</P>
<P>
   ---
B.C. Tobacco Ban Public Hearings To Open
</P>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- When the provincial Workers'
Compensation Board imposed tough anti-smoking regulations across
the province in January, it ignited a fiery protest from smokers
and the businesses that serve them.
</P>
<P>
   All are gearing up for another showdown at public hearings that
begin Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We expect to be railroaded with a policy that they've already
drafted,'' said Dave Crown, vice president of the Liquor Licensees
and Retailers Association of British Columbia
</P>
<P>
   The short-lived British Columbia regulations were among the
toughest in North America, banning smoking in bars, restaurants,
casinos, long-term care facilities and even provincial jails.
</P>
<P>
   But after the regulations were in place for only three months, a
British Columbia Supreme Court judge struck the policy down in
March, saying the ban was enacted without proper consultation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
