<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pacers Lead Lakers 79-66 After 3Q  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- A boisterous home crowd and the resurgence
of Reggie Miller helped the Indiana Pacers take a 79-66 lead over
the Los Angeles Lakers through three quarters of Game 3 of the NBA
Finals on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant's sprained left ankle kept him out of the Lakers'
lineup, and Miller capitalized by scoring 25 points in a barrage of
outside shots and drives.
</P>
<P>
   Amid deafening chants of ''REG-GIE! REG-GIE!'', Miller hit a
long jumper and a 3-pointer late in the third quarter to give the
Pacers an 18-point lead. The star guard played every minute of the
first three quarters as Indiana moved within 12 minutes of cutting
Los Angeles' series lead to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles won the first two games of the best-of-seven series
at Staples Center. Sunday's contest was the first home Finals game
ever played by the Pacers, who won three championships in the ABA.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal started slowly again but had 26 points and
seven rebounds through three quarters. The Lakers too often settled
for jump shots and failed to pound the ball inside to O'Neal, who
was 12-for-20 from the field through three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The league MVP, who averaged 41.5 points and 21.5 rebounds in
the first two games of the Finals, got just one shot in the game's
first 11 minutes and wasn't getting the prime low-post position he
claimed in the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, no one stepped up to fill the Lakers' offensive
void created by Bryant's absence. Robert Horry had eight points off
the bench through three quarters, while starting guards Brian Shaw
and Ron Harper had six points apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was 1-for-16 from the field in Game 1 and scored two
points in the fourth quarter of Game 2, but he had 16 points at
halftime Sunday as Indiana led 53-42. Miller and Jalen Rose made
consecutive fast-break layups in the final 24 seconds of the first
half, but Glen Rice hit a 3-pointer with 0.7 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers couldn't score and committed five fouls in the first
three minutes after halftime, and Los Angeles quickly cut Indiana's
lead to 57-52.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana then made a 12-0 run capped by a 3-pointer from Sam
Perkins. Rose had 19 points on 9-of-15 shooting through three
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers, one of the league's worst rebounding teams during
the regular season, outrebounded Los Angeles 29-20 through three
quarters. Rik Smits and Dale Davis drew most of the defensive
assignments against O'Neal, but the Pacers also sent double- and
triple-teams much more frequently than in the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw was no replacement for Bryant, shooting 3-of-8 for six
points in the first half and getting beaten regularly on defense by
Miller. Bryant, presumably receiving treatment on his ankle, was
not even in street clothes on the Lakers' bench.
</P>
<P>
   The players were much more feisty than in the first two games,
with Davis and Horry exchanging stares and shoves after Horry threw
the ball hard at Davis while falling out of bounds in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Dual technicals were later called on Mark Jackson and Harper
when the two shoved the ball at each other. Derek Fisher and Austin
Croshere extended their mutual dislike, with Croshere committing a
flagrant foul by nearly tackling Fisher to prevent a second-quarter
layup and Fisher shoving him away in response.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, the Pacers played a video clip of Gene
Hackman's speech before the final game in the film ''Hoosiers,'' as
well as a message from Indianapolis native David Letterman, who
urged the Pacers to ''make Daddy proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Davis, traded by the Pacers to Toronto last summer,
watched from a courtside seat and got a standing ovation when shown
on the video board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 2139 </TRAILER>
