<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former hostage at U.S. Embassy in Iran, dead at 65  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HOMOSASSA, Fla. (AP) - Bert C. Moore, a history teacher whose
career change to the foreign service led him to become one of 52
Americans held hostage at the U.S. Embassy in Iran from 1979 to
1981, has died. He was 65.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, who moved to Homosassa two years ago from Mount Vernon,
Ohio, died of cancer at his home on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Moore received a bachelor's degree in education from Ohio State
University and a master's degree in Public Administration from
Syracuse University. From 1957 to 1960, he taught American history
and world history at Mount Vernon High School.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, Moore was appointed as a foreign service officer in the
U.S. Department of State.
</P>
<P>
   During his foreign service career, Moore served in Washington
and at U.S. embassies and consulates in Canada, Rhodesia, Malawi,
France, Zaire, Iran, Spain, Nigeria, Indonesia and India.
</P>
<P>
   For being one of the Americans held hostage in Tehran, Iran,
during the Islamic fundamentalist revolution, Moore received the
Christian A. Herter Award in 1981 for extraordinary contributions
to the practice of diplomacy and the Department of State Award for
Valor that same year. In 1985, he received a Presidential
Meritorious Award.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring from the Senior Foreign Service in 1990 as a
minister counselor of the United States, Moore continued to work on
short term assignments for the Department of State.
</P>
<P>
   Moore is survived by his wife, Marjorie; sons David Moore of
Lake Los Angeles, Calif., Bob Moore of Chatham, N.J., and Charles
Moore, Barton, N.Y.; daughter, Diane Wilkie, Lincroft, N.J.;
brother, Raymond Moore of Newark, Ohio; half-brother, Roby Watson
Jr. of Michigan; and five grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
