<DOCNO> APW20000611.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fourth county joins push for Southern Tier rail authority  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BATH, N.Y. (AP) - Steuben County this week became the fourth of
four counties eager for a state-designated railroad authority to
revive the Southern Tier Extension.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation pending in Albany would create a four-county
organization that would take over the 146-mile railroad that
extends from Hornell to the Pennsylvania line near Corry, Pa. and
has the distinction of being the shortest rail route between New
York and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Other counties seeking the authority are Chautauqua, Cattaraugus
and Allegany.
</P>
<P>
   Area leaders cite a range of possibilities, from new economic
development to the dream of local passenger rail service.
</P>
<P>
   Stoner Horey, Steuben County's legislative chairman, said the
Southern Tier Extension could provide a ''release valve'' for
congested rail traffic on the northern rail line from Albany to
Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ''It (could) restore the east-west transportation route that's
been moribund for years,'' Horey said.
</P>
<P>
   The authority would assume ownership of the line from Norfolk
Southern, which along with CSX Corp. has been troubled by service
and safety problems - as well as plummeting stock prices -
resulting from their June 1, 1999 breakup of Conrail, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ''Norfolk Southern has let it be known they are not interested
in upgrading the route,'' Horey said, adding that the company
probably wouldn't mind shedding its approximately $2 million
property tax burden for the route.
</P>
<P>
   The authority would be tax exempt.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-member authority would consist of three members from each
county. Already $1.1 million in federal intermodal transport funds
administered by the state appears set aside for upgrades on a route
that has deteriorated over the past 25 years. Horey said all that
was needed now was the state Legislature's nod.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of the state's authorities, this one would not have
borrowing power, which would have been a sticking point for a
governor criticized like his predecessors for ''backdoor''
borrowing by authorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-11-00 2203 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000611.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Cup Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Canada advanced to the
semifinals of
regional qualifying for the 2002 World Cup, playing a scoreless tie
with Cuba on Sunday night to advance 1-0 in the home-and-home,
total-goals playoff.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After winning 1-0 on June 4 at Havana, Canada knew going in it
would advance with a scoreless tie and, despite missing several
scoring chances, extended its unbeaten streak to 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   Canada, which hasn't qualified for the World Cup since 1986,
joins Group C of the semifinals in the North and Central American
and Caribbean region, where it will play a double round-robin
series with Mexico, Panama and Trinidad and Tobago starting next
month.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's other game, Guillermo Ramirez scored in the 32nd
minute, leading Guatemala over Antigua and Barbuda 1-0 in the first
leg of their playoff.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of that series advances to Group E, where it will
join the United States, Costa Rica and Barbados.
</P>
<P>
   The top two nations in each of the three semifinal groups group
advance to the six-nation finals of the CONCACAF region, which will
produce three qualifiers for the 32-nation tournament, to be played
in Japan and South Korea in 2002. The United States had a bye until
the semifinals of qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   Guatemala played Sunday at St. John's, Antigua. The second leg
of the Antigua-Guatemala series is scheduled for next weekend at
Guatemala City.
</P>
<P>
   ''We missed our chances,'' said Antigua coach Zoran Varnesh,
upset his team missed three good first-half chances.
</P>
<P>
   The third semifinal group includes El Salvador, St. Vincent and
the Grenadines, and the winner of the Haiti-Honduras playoff.
Honduras won 4-0 last week in the first leg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
