<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solomons Cease-Fire End Feared  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM FOREMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONIARA, Solomon Islands (AP) -- A new group of militants gunned
down a man Sunday in the Solomon Islands, officials said, a killing
that diplomats feared could end a fragile cease-fire and spark
another cycle of revenge attacks in the South Pacific nation.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting came as a new wave of foreign tourists and workers,
many pushing carts piled high with luggage, lined up at the airport
in the capital, Honiara to be evacuated. At a nearby port, hundreds
of local residents squeezed on board crowded ferries, fleeing the
city to other provinces.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the evacuations, Honiara appeared relatively calm. No
gunfire could be heard, as in past days, and armed rebels who
seized the prime minister and took control of the capital last week
were no longer cruising the capital's streets.
</P>
<P>
   But the fatal shooting Sunday in Gizo, the capital of Western
Province, appeared to be politically motivated and stirred fears of
new violence in Honiara.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the killing were sketchy because telephone service in
Gizo was down, but a rebel leader and local media blamed the death
on militants from Bougainville, an island in Papua New Guinea.
Bougainville was the scene of a 10-year secessionist war that
killed thousands before a 1998 cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ''I suspect they are offering themselves as mercenaries,'' said
Andrew Nori, a former lawmaker and leader of rebels from the island
of Malaita.
</P>
<P>
   The militants' mission ''is to evict the Malaitans from the
Western Province,'' Nori said, adding that the victim was Malaitan.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking the Malaitans off the main island of Guadalcanal has
also been the goal of the Isatabus. During the past 18 months, the
Isatabus have forced about 20,000 migrant Malaitans back to
Malaita.
</P>
<P>
   Angry that they have received no compensation for their losses,
the Malaitans have taken up arms and demanded the resignation of
Prime Minister Bartholomew Ulufa'alu. The leader faces a vote of no
confidence in the parliament on Thursday. Ulufa'alu is a Malaitan,
but his people accuse him of being too soft on the Isatabus.
</P>
<P>
   If lawmakers vote to keep Ulufa'alu in office, many fear that
the Malaitans will refuse to handover their weapons and instead use
them to stage another coup. Although Nori is believed to want
peace, it was unclear how much influence he had over rebels who are
growing bolder after their recent successes.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand's foreign minister, Phil Goff, said Monday that
Ulufa'alu is worried about being killed by the rebels and would
probably step down within days. Goff was part of a delegation that
visited the Solomon Islands over the weekend to seek a solution to
the political crisis and rebel warring.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a situation in the Solomons where a prime minister is
in fear of his life ... who will resign this week, I am sure,
because the cost of staying in power ... is too great,'' Goff said
in Wellington, New Zealand's capital.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels, or Malaita Eagle Force, have been trying to win the
public over by keeping order in Honiaria, where looting and other
lawlessness have been rare. Police said the fighters have taken
over police duties and even use Honiaria's jail to lock up rebels
who have misbehaved.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have our guns and everything, so we're just sitting back
and relaxing,'' said police Sgt. Alec Toata, pointing to a long,
empty rifle rack in the main police station. ''People now call
them, not us.''
</P>
<P>
   Up the street from the police station, rebels with teeth stained
red from chewing betel nut, a mild stimulant, lounge around in lawn
chairs outside their barracks, a drab office building they seized
from the provincial government of Guadalcanal.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a baseball cap with the word ''Police'' on it, rebel
Charles Addix stood behind a counter in a small office and helped a
woman file a claim for luggage lost on a ferry boat. He dismissed
the exodus of people from the capital as irrational panic and said
they would return in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Foreigners should feel safe here,'' Addix said. ''Our problem
is only with the Isatabu Freedom Movement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 2230 </TRAILER>
