<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Witnesses Recall La. Church Terror  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GONZALES, La. (AP) -- There haven't been regular services at the
New St. John Fellowship Church since March 10, 1999, the day
prosecutors say Shon Miller walked through the church doors, fired
two shots into the ceiling and asked, ''Who's going to save you
now?''
</P>
<P>
   Jurors hearing Miller's trial on four counts of murder and four
of attempted murder walked through those same doors on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, church deacon Donald Ray Smith recounted for the jury
what he saw that night, starting with Miller's 2-year-old son, Shon
Jr., turning in his seat and with a big smile saying, ''Daddy!'' as
Miller walked in.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, 23, answered: ''Son, don't call me Daddy now,'' Smith
told the jury. Then, he said, Miller opened fire, hitting and
killing his wife, Carla Vessel Miller, 25, Shon Jr., and Vaniaro
Jackson, 19.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Miller reloaded and continued firing into Carla
Miller's body. Other witnesses, four of whom were wounded during
the shooting, testified in court to the same events.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who was paralyzed from the waist down by a shot from a
deputy's gun, didn't return to the church with the jury.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to be there. I've had enough nightmares about it
already,'' Miller told District Judge Alvin Turner Jr.
</P>
<P>
   His trial was to resume Monday. Prosecutors are seeking the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's attorney, Raymond Gautreau, said in opening statements
that Miller was in an alcohol-induced blackout at time of shootings
and doesn't remember them.
</P>
<P>
   His attempt last week to change Miller's plea from innocent to
innocent by reason of insanity was denied.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the charges involving the seven parishioners,
Miller is charged with killing his mother-in-law, Mildred Vessel,
53, as she sat in her van in front of her house, a short way from
the church.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier that day, Carla Miller told her estranged husband she
had filed for divorce, prosecutor Robin O'Bannon told the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Miller had viciously beaten his wife, slashed
her car tires and burned her mobile home after they separated.
</P>
<P>
   Seven bullets were found in her body after it was removed from
the church.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was intense with a fury. He moved with nimble feet. His
eyes ... fury came out with every gunshot,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ''His eyes were red and he looked like he was 20 feet tall,''
said Rebecca Delpit, 38. She said she was protecting her baby and
praying when Miller shot her. The bullet went in her shoulder and
is still lodged in her neck, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was found soon after the shootings in a shed at a home
less than a mile from the church.
</P>
<P>
   Police spent an hour trying to persuade Miller to surrender
while he pointed his gun at himself and talked of voices telling
him commit suicide and hurt others, officials said. When police
stormed in, one officer fell and his pistol went off. The bullet
lodged near Miller's spine, paralyzing him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 2236 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000611.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fugitive Paraguayan Arrested  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Brazilian police on Sunday
arrested a former Paraguayan army chief wanted in connection with
last year's assassination of his country's vice president,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Lino Oviedo was arrested at a friend's apartment in Foz do
Iguacu, on Brazil's southwestern border with Paraguay and
Argentina. The popular tourist resort is 800 miles southwest of Rio
de Janeiro but just 220 miles east of Asuncion, the capital of
Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   A federal police agent, who asked not to be identified,
confirmed the arrest but said he could not provide further details.
</P>
<P>
   Oviedo had been sought for his alleged involvement in the 1999
murder of Paraguay's Vice President Luis Argana.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say the assassination of Argana occurred after
Oviedo was released from a Paraguayan jail, where he served just 6
months of a 10-year sentence in connection with a failed coup in
1996. After the murder, Oviedo first fled to Argentina, where he
was granted political asylum, before going to Brazil. The ex-army
chief is also blamed for another failed coup in Paraguay on May 18.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his capture, police found a loaded revolver in
the apartment, but Oviedo did not resist the arrest, Globonews
television reported.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities had been searching the southern border since the
beginning of the month in hopes of finding Oviedo, who had sought
protection from arrest and possible extradition through his lawyers
in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   An order for Oviedo's arrest had been issued at the request of
the Paraguayan government. Argana's family had offered a $100,000
reward for his capture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 2258 </TRAILER>
