<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, June 11, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Study: Most Death Row Cases Flawed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two-thirds of death penalty cases that were appealed from
1973 through 1995 were successful, report researchers who contend the nation's
capital punishment system is ''collapsing under the weight of its own
mistakes.'' A study of 4,578 appeals during those years showed that most cases
''are so seriously flawed that they have to be done over again,'' said Columbia
University law professor James Liebman, the lead author. The study comes at a
time of increased debate over capital punishment. Earlier this year, Republican
Gov. George Ryan of Illinois imposed a moratorium on capital punishment in his
state after 13 death row inmates were exonerated.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Attack Reported on Solomon Islands
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HONIARA, Solomon Islands (AP) -- A new group of militants gunned down a man
Sunday in the Solomon Islands, officials said, a killing that diplomats feared
could end a fragile cease-fire and spark another cycle of revenge attacks in the
South Pacific nation. The shooting came as a new wave of foreign tourists and
workers, many pushing carts piled high with luggage, lined up at the airport in
the capital, Honiara to be evacuated. Despite the evacuations, Honiara appeared
relatively calm. No gunfire could be heard, as in past days, and armed rebels
who seized the prime minister and took control of the capital last week were no
longer cruising the capital's streets.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Web Attracts Younger News Audience
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new poll on media trends says key segments of the
nation's news audience, particularly younger and better-educated Americans, and
those seeking financial information, are turning increasingly to the Internet.
The Web's rapid growth as a source for news continues a splintering of that
audience among the Internet, cable and broadcast television, and print
publications. A third of the public now goes online for news at least once a
week, compared to a fifth two years ago, according to a Pew Research poll.
Fifteen percent get daily reports from the Internet, almost three times the
number two years ago.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bashar Ascension May Set Precedent
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Bashar Assad's imminent rise to the presidency of Syria
could turn an idea many Arab leaders have nurtured for years into a precedent:
grooming their sons to establish ''republican dynasties'' to ensure that power
remains in the family after they're gone. The transition of power from father to
son has gone smoothly in Jordan, Morocco, Bahrain and Qatar -- all monarchies.
Before President Hafez Assad's death Saturday, the phenomenon had never been
tried in a republic.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Alaska Air Pilot Doubted Safety
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- A veteran Alaska Airlines pilot wrote a letter to a company
executive saying he was worried about the safety of an airplane he flew May 30
and suggesting the company needs to improve its maintenance. Capt. David
Crawley, who has flown Alaska Airlines planes since 1984, told the executive he
became deeply concerned after reviewing maintenance reports on the MD-80 he flew
that day from Los Angeles to Seattle, The Seattle Times reported today. ''As we
accelerated down the runway, I thought about how all this would look for Alaska
Airlines if this airplane did not make it to Seattle,'' Crawley wrote.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
NAACP Head Shinhoster Dies in Crash
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- Earl T. Shinhoster, who was acting executive
director of the NAACP in the early 1990s, died in a car crash today at age 47.
The driver of a car Shinhoster was riding in apparently lost control after a
tire blew out off Interstate 85 near Milstead, about 25 miles east of
Montgomery, said Cpl. Damon Summers. The car went off the interstate,
overturned, and hit a tree, killing Shinhoster. Shinhoster, a Savannah, Ga.
native, was the director of the NAACP's People's Voter Empowerment project, a
national voter registration and education program. Shinhoster was with the NAACP
for 30 years, and served in several senior positions, including national field
secretary.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell Monday after Friday's decline in the Dow
Jones industrial average. The Nikkei fell 55.77 points to 16,806.14 in early
trading. On Friday, the average closed down 142.43 points.
</P>
