<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 23:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Miller's Free Throws Holds Off LA  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE HERMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Reggie Miller still doesn't have a
fourth-quarter field goal in the NBA Finals. This time, his free
throws were good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whenever you play, you've got to take as many free points as
possible,'' said Miller, who made all eight of his free throw
attempts in the final period as the Indiana Pacers held off Los
Angeles 100-91 Sunday night. The victory cut the Lakers' lead in
the best-of-seven series to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ''They way they're guarding me, I don't get a lot of wide-open
looks, a lot of easy looks. When I get to the free throw line, I've
got to make them,'' said Miller, who is 20-for-20 from the foul
line in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Miller made half of his 22 field goal attempts Sunday night, but
he took only one shot -- which he missed -- in the fourth quarter. In
a seven-point loss in Game 2, he took only two shots -- which he
also missed -- in the final period. He was scoreless in the fourth
quarter of Game 1, in which he finished with a playoff career-low
seven points.
</P>
<P>
   ''We like to get Reggie off the picks, but I think Reggie wore
down a little bit. You could see he didn't have the energy he did
earlier,'' said coach Larry Bird, who rested Miller only at the
start of the fourth quarter. ''But Reggie came through. He scored
33 points, and we need him to do that in the next game. We know
they're going to bounce back even harder the next time.''
</P>
<P>
   Game 4 will be Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of guys were very emotional tonight,'' Bird said. ''You
waste a lot of energy when you do that. But we battled today,
unlike the first game we played.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who had promised to be more aggressive with the series
in friendly Conseco Fieldhouse, had 16 points in the first half,
when the Pacers took a 53-42 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll rest when I'm dead,'' he said. ''This is the most
important game for us. We have to get back in the series.''
</P>
<P>
   With an 11-2 first-half run, including a rebound tip and a
3-pointer by Miller, the Pacers did just that. The big streak
followed the last of four early ties and put the Pacers up 19-10.
The Indiana defense, meanwhile, repeatedly double-teamed Shaquille
O'Neal every time he touched the ball, allowing him just two shots
and five points in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal finished with 33 points, but -- unlike Miller -- he was
just 3-of-13 from the free throw line.
</P>
<P>
   ''We came down hard on Shaq,'' Bird said. ''In the second half,
they got us in some trouble by going inside and then back out, but
we did a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller scored Indiana's first three baskets of the second
quarter, including a three-point play as he was fouled by O'Neal.
Austin Croshere, the steadiest reserve off the Indiana bench
through the series, matched a 3-pointer by Rick Fox and added three
free throws for a 38-26 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana's biggest lead in the first half was at 42-27 on a
rebound basket by Dale Davis, his only points of the game to go
along with 12 rebounds. The Pacers built it to 18 in the second
half before a final run by the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our defense picked up and we controlled the boards,'' Bird
said of the 39-33 Indiana edge in rebounding. ''We gave in a couple
times, but we were getting a little fatigued. But we made the
effort, and that was the key.''
</P>
<P>
   Jalen Rose added 21 points for the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted to come out earlier a little bit stronger,'' Rose
said. ''We get a lot of our energy off the crowd, and we made it
happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-11-00 2303 </TRAILER>
