<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> K.C. Pitcher Wants To Avoid Surgery  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Ailing Kansas City Royals pitcher Jose
Rosado is not convinced that surgery is necessary, and wants to
maintain his rehabilitation program for now.
</P>
<P>
   Rosado said Saturday that if he makes no progress in another
month, he'll undergo arthroscopic surgery on his left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got time,'' Rosado said. ''I'll keep battling.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors recently performed a dye-enhanced MRI on Rosado's
shoulder. Tests were not conclusive, but they indicated a cartilage
abnormality in the back of his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Royals general manager Herk Robinson described it as a fraying,
something not uncommon for major league pitchers. Robinson said
he'd like Rosado ''to make every effort to work through it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''When you're at this level, you don't want to have surgery if
you don't have to,'' the 25-year-old Rosado said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosado, a two-time All-Star, entered this season as the team's
No. 1 starter. But he was slowed by hamstring problems in spring
training and never found his rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after laboring through five starts with a 2-2 record
and 5.86 ERA, Rosado landed on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ''I put too much pressure on my arm,'' Rosado said. ''I kept
saying, 'It's going to go away.' But I wasn't helping my team.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosado would like to travel with the team on the next road trip,
but it's more likely that manager Tony Muser will send him to
Florida to work on conditioning and throwing drills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
